The end board should be 2 Flare Metals, the 4 link Darkness Metal, and Borreload Savage Dragon with a Red Eyes Fang with Chain. 

7/10 I get full combo with more than half those times with back ups and ways to handle Maxx "C", and Ash. Loses hard to Nib tho so that's why it's not too competative.

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Gabriel "Timelo" Nill

Tournament: YCS Dortmund - November 12th 2022

Placement: Top 64

It's simple, Eldlich with extra beatsticks.

If you want to chop down to 40 cards, I'd suggest dropping the 3x Torrential and 2x Dark Bribe. But I would recommend replacing the 3x Solemn Strike with 3x Solemn Judgment.

Extra deck is built to support both Branded and Eldlich, however you won't rely too much on the 3 Eldlich cards (Constellar and the 2 trains) as the power mainly comes from your branded fusions and Eldlich/Heavenly.

Keep in mind, Heavenly CAN be used on either turn so it's an easy additional body on the field when they activate a facedown backrow card. Even better when it's been revealed on the previous turn, as you get a +1 in your backrow which is huge advantage for Eldlich style play as you can set ANY spell or trap (although it cannot be activated the same turn, standard ruling applies).

I wouldn't expect to top any tournaments. But this is a nice budget power hungry deck for casual, or maybe even competitive play in some scenes.

Side deck is built to counter mirror matches and current meta (tears) with Shadow-Imprisoning Mirror hurting tear cards nicely and Heavy Duster storm a great backrow removal. Galaxy Cyclone is specifically for removing those gritty cards like Mystic Mine (ew) as it can be activated in the GY.

Not so great against Runick though so, gl if you vs them as they just banish all your stuff.

 

PS. You could probably throw some more Branded stuff and bump up to a 60 card deck for a real mixer, clock out the Eldlich extra deck stuff for Branded things like Masquerade for the burn, but I haven't thought that deeply about this.

 

Enjoy

deck_name: The Phantom Knights of Scythe Lock
deck_excerpt: Oh, they banned Rhongo? Verte, DPE, Dagda, Scythe, & Adventure are still in the game => Phantom Knights are still full power.
deck_description:
The Phantom Knights of Scythe Lock

Phantom Knights may have lost Number 86: Heroic Champion - Rhongomyniad (63504681) in Master Duel, but with Predaplant Verte Anaconda (70369116), Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer (60461804), Artifact Dagda (7480763), Artifact Scythe (20292186), and the entire Adventure engine still legal, it hardly shifts the power of Phantom Knights in a best-of-one format. We even recently got The Phantom Knights of Torn Scales (25538345) back at 3. The banlist hits for Adventure don't really effect this deck either, as Water Enchantress of the Temple (30680659) can be accessed at any time due to it being a target for Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss (58699500). This deck can consistently, every game, even through moderate interruption, put out a board with a negate, DPE, and lock your opponent out of their extra deck, then have the resources to make Accesscode Talker (86066372) and kill your opponent when your turn comes back around. The deck is also really powerful going second as the Adventure cards help a lot with saving the week parts of your combo and dealing with your opponent's threats.

Deck Guide

Typical Combo Going First:

1. Get 2 level 3 monsters on the field. (Normal summon Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring (14558127) if you have to.) Attempt to get The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine (98827725) in hand if you can using PK GY effects for future plays.

2. Make Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss (58699500). After Cherubini is summoned, avoid special summoning to zones he points to, except for Link monsters.

3. Send Water Enchantress of the Temple (30680659) for cost. Because it is sent as a cost, your opponent cannot actually interact with Cherubini at all to prevent this from happening, other than by somehow destroying it before you activate its effect.

4. Banish Water Enchantress of the Temple (30680659) from GY to add Rite of Aramesir (3285551) to hand.

5. Activate Rite of Aramesir (3285551) and activate Fateful Adventure (39568067) from deck.

6. Normal/special summon a monster any way you can to trigger Fateful Adventure (39568067), add Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon (38745520) to hand. Do not equip it yet.

7. Activate Fateful Adventure (39568067) to add Wandering Gryphon Rider (2563463) to hand, then send Dracoback, the Rideable Dragon (38745520) to grave. Activate its effect to equip itself to token. Special summon Gryphon Rider.

8. Get another monster on the field any way you can. Use any two monsters other than Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss (58699500), Wandering Gryphon Rider (2563463), or the token to make Artifact Dagda (7480763).

9. Activate The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine (98827725), searched from any PK effect or from starting hand, then chain Artifact Dagda (7480763) to set Artifact Scythe (20292186) from deck.

10. Link The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine (98827725) for Link Spider (98978921). This is done because Predaplant Verte Anaconda (70369116) specifically requires Effect Monsters, and Shade Brigande is treated as Normal Monster.

11. Use Link Spider (98978921) and Artifact Dagda (7480763) to make Predaplant Verte Anaconda (70369116), use its effect to activate the effect of Fusion Destiny (52947044) to special summon Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer (60461804) to zone Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss (58699500) is pointing to, this gives it destruction immunity (even from its own effect).

12. Set relevant spells/traps, end turn.

13. In opponent's Draw or Standy Phase, activate Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer (60461804) effect to pop itself and the set Artifact Scythe (20292186). Opponent can no longer special summon from the Extra Deck, you still have a negate on Wandering Gryphon Rider (2563463), and your DPE and Predaplant Verte Anaconda (70369116) are immune to destruction. If opponent tries to attack Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss (58699500), you can send Verte to GY to protect it, as it can be useful in future turns.

Notes:

  • If you open cards that start the Adventure engine, you can send any PK card you need in the GY by the effect of Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss (58699500).
  • If you open Fusion Destiny (52947044) in starting hand, the typical best play is to use Artifact Dagda (7480763), Link Spider (98978921), and Wandering Gryphon Rider (2563463) to make a 3-material Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess (4280258) for 3 monster negates instead of a single omni-negate, then activate Fusion Destiny at the very end of your turn.
  • Feel free to use Wandering Gryphon Rider (2563463)'s effect to negate any interruptions that could prematurely end your combo, especially Nibiru, the Primal Being (27204311) if you did not open Crossout Designator (65681983).
  • When going second, your primary goal is to get to get enough monsters on field to Knightmare Unicorn (38342335) and any other one monster, while dealing with your opponent's threats as you do so to make Accesscode Talker (86066372). Then, with whatever remaining resources you have, attempt to make Predaplant Verte Anaconda (70369116) with any two monsters to summon Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer (60461804) and attack for game with DPE and Accesscode. If things go poorly, try to attack with a The Phantom Knights of Break Sword (62709239) boosted by The Phantom Knights of Ragged Gloves (63821877) in the Battle Phase. In MP2, rank it up into Downerd Magician (72167543) then into Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder (90448279) for 2 Quick-Effect non-once-per-turn board wipes. You should be set from there.

Card Choice Explanations:

1 Nibiru, the Primal Being (27204311) - We play one copy of Nibiru as a target for Crossout Designator (65681983) as the Phantom Knights can be weak to a well-timed Nibiru (though the Adventure Engine does wonders to alleviate this problem), and to draw into when our opponent is attempting to play through our Maxx "C" (23434538). I run it at one because I do not want to see it in my starting hand.

1 Destiny HERO - Dasher (81866673) - I debated a lot between running Dasher or Destiny HERO - Malicious (9411399) as a Fusion Destiny (52947044) target, and although Malicious is better than Dasher on future turns, it requires you to run an extra brick which hurts the deck's consistency significantly for a very low benefit considering games end so quickly in this meta, so I decided on Dasher instead.

1 The Phantom Knights of Stained Greaves (88544390) - Most PK decks do not run this card when not utilizing a Rank 4 Xyz engine, so it may be confusing to see it here. Because this card provides an extra special summon on a new name, it has come in clutch in more games than I can count. Having hands excessively clogged by Phantom Knights names feels really bad, and this card is an effective way to turn that issue into a benefit. Its run at 1 because of the numerous ways to get it into your graveyard with the engine.

3 The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak (90432163) - Most PK decklists will only run 2 of Ancient Cloak, but this is honestly my favorite normal summon in the deck (due to Adventure engine locking you out of The Phantom Knights of Torn Scales (25538345)'s effect when normal summoned), and therefore I want to see it in my opening hand, hence running it at three.

Card Alternatives

1 Psychic Tracker (30227494), 1 Psychic Wheeleder (3233859), 2 Emergency Teleport (67723438) - I use this small Psychic engine to get to Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss (58699500) more easily, which is the key to your entire deck. This can be substituted for a Danger engine if you prefer: run 3 Danger!? Tsuchinoko? (99745551) and 1 Danger!? Jackalope? (43694650). This engine can provide some free graveyard access and some card draw, which are both very useful, but I've found I'm not lucky enough for it, as I frequently get my PK traps in the grave which shuts down the effect of The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine (98827725).

1 Destiny HERO - Dasher (81866673) - If you prefer, you can switch out Dasher and 1 other card from the deck (your preference) for 2 Destiny HERO - Malicious (9411399), which gives you a more easily accessible special summon the turn after using Fusion Destiny (52947044).

1 Leviair the Sea Dragon (95992081) - This card is only particularly significant in the grind game in a scenario where you are beginning to run out of resources. In the modern metagame (especially for this deck), this is fairly rare. So if you wish, you can swap Leviair for the Rank 4 Xyz engine and run Time Thief Redoer (55285840), who is a powerful boss monster in his own right and is very useful in a scenario where your Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer (60461804) has been outed.
This build is especially good against Ishizu Tears. Doing lots of testing online and had huge succes against them.

deck_name: Fury from the deep structure deck

deck_description:
This archetype needs new support to keep it from sucking, which is sad, given that it used to be pretty good.

Feedback is always welcome.

Well, you read the title. You know what's deck this is. And yes, you saw an Ishizu Shaddoll deck with absolutely NO Tearlaments. This deck does well going first or going second. However, going first may be preferable so you can get Gravekeeper's Trap and/or Shaddoll Schism on board. 

 

And thanks to Reeshaddoll Wendi and Shaddoll Falco's floating effects, it's easy to get Shaddolls on board after using the Ishizu cards to set up your Graveyard and give yourself some field presence. For that reason, one of the Link Monsters chosen for this deck is Proxy F Magician, which can fusion summon using monsters from your field once per turn.

 

Furthermore, because Agido and Kelbek are both EARTH Monsters, you can use them and a Shaddoll monster to summon El Shaddoll Shekhinaga, and mill at least 5 cards in the process. Shekhinaga also makes a good Super Poly target if you're playing against an EARTH Deck or facing an EARTH floodgate like Naturia Beast or Barrier Statue of the Droughts.

deck_excerpt: Want to play competitively but sick of Tearlaments? Try out Naturia Ishizu!
deck_description:
The TCG Yugioh scene changed forever November 4, 2022 with the release of Magnificent Mavens. Ishizu cards arrived in the set, pushing to the T0 brink the deck that will dominate the meta - Tearlaments Ishizu. Nowadays, only decks that shut off the graveyard or work with the graveyard mills can offer a fighting chance vs. this "Tear Zero" format, and one of those decks are Naturia Ishizu!


Naturia Ishizu fills a decent niche in this mermaid-dominated Yugioh ecosystem. What are the reasons you should you play this deck? There are plenty! 

 

  • Naturia can plus off mills (so you can piggyback and generate advantage when your opponent mills with Ishizu cards. You can play on "turn 0" just like Tearlaments). 
  • Naturia are earth type (effectively dodging being banished by Bystial cards, and can be searched/milled/resurrected with Vernusylph cards). 
  • Naturia's end board is extremely strong and oppressive (Naturia Beast/Barkion + Sunflower nearly infinitely negates, spells, traps and monsters respectively). 
  • Naturia, Vernusylph and Ishizu search, resurrect, recur and mill each other (this deck's archetypes seem to be long lost lovers for each other, d'awww how cute :3). 
Best of all, it ISN'T TEARLAMENTS, but IT CAN COMPETE with Tearlaments! Why play boring and mind-numbing Tear mirrors when you can play a unique deck that is spicy, interesting and competitive!? So if you're sick of all the mermaids, this is the deck for you!

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 

  • Forming the deck’s core strategy, the Naturia cards in the Main Deck consist of 16 cards:

3 Camellia, 3 Molcricket, 1 Stinkbug, 1 Sunflower, 1 Horneedle, 3 Blessing and 3 Sacred Tree. 1 One for One acts as another copy of Molcricket, the main starter of the Naturia archetype.  In the Extra Deck there are 1 Beast, and 1 Barkion.

  • The milling and GY manipulation powerhouses of this deck, the Ishizu cards in the maindeck consists of whopping 19 cards:

3 Keldo, 3 Kelbek, 3 Mudora, 3 Agido and 1 Gravekeeper's Trap. 3 Diviner of the Heralds and 3 Herald of Orange Light enable disruption and further milling with the Ishizu cards. 

  • Each functioning as a monster reborn of an earth monster, Vernusylph cards assist the Naturia strategy and consist of 9 cards.

3 Awakening Forests, 3 Flourishing Hills, and 3 Misting Seedlings. 

  • Board Breakers, Support and Handtraps cards consist of 11 cards.

3 Kashtira Fenrir, 3 Bystial Magnamhut, 1 Druiswyrm, 1 Foolish Burial, 1 Called by the Grave and 2 Pot of Desires. 

55 cards are used in this deck since the milling ability of this deck (and possibly your opponent's deck) makes every key card easily accessible through GY recovery like Vernusylph cards, the Ishizu shufflers and Naturia Blessing. 17+ cards directly or indirectly mill cards to the GY in Naturia Ishizu, so the GY remains readily accessible for plays. 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN

 

Going first, the gameplan is to generally set up a board consisting of Naturia Beast, Molcricket, Camellia and possibly Sunflower, given you have an extender. Any other cards (depending on what you draw/mill) can turn into a rank 4 of your choice (ideally in this format, Abyss Dweller.) or a level 10 Synchro. This end board results in almost infinite spell negates (Beast), up to 3 monster negates (Sunflower) and a GY effect lockdown with Abyss Dweller. The graveyard can have Mudora and Keldo to shuffle back your opponent's GY as additional interruption. This is generally enough to stop any GY deck in it's tracks so that an OTK can be achieved next turn with Naturia Ishizu's relentless monster spam.


If you've been interrupted too much by handtraps/turn 0 interruptions, get Bagooska out to stall for additional resources and an ideal gamestate. 

This deck's combos are non-linear, draw-dependent and mill-dependent. This deck's one main combo line features a singular Molcricket. This one card combo grants access to Naturia Beast, and a Molcricket for next turn's follow-up. 
  1. Normal summon Molcricket. 
  2. Tribute Molcricket for Camellia. 
  3. Activate Camillia's on-summon effect to mill Sacred Tree from deck to grave. 
  4. Sacred Tree searches Blessing. 
  5. Activate Naturia Blessing to resurrect Molcricket. 
  6. Synchro Camellia + Molcricket for Naturia Beast. 
  7. Activate Molcricket's trigger effect in the GY to summon itself once a Naturia Extra Deck monster is summoned. If you have extra extenders such as Vernusylph cards or additional Naturia blessing, try to get Sunflower and Camellia on the field, since they all represent extra monster negate fodder for Naturia Sunflower to use. 
As for graveyard set-up, Ishizu + Vernusylph cards facilitate that. Every Vernusylph monster discards a monster for it's activation, and Agido/Kelbek are ideal targets to discard, since they both mill 5. Funfact, since Awakening Forests sends to GY from deck any earth monster, if you already have Kelbek + Agido in hand, you can discard it with Awakening Forests' effect to send the other Izshizu card from the deck to mill 10!

Normal summoning Diviner of Heralds also sends to GY Agido/Kelbek for a mill 5. This would make her a level 6 tuner, and pairing her up with a level 4 makes a level 10 Synchro of your choice! 

Going second, opponent's boards are broken by interrupting your opponent at key moments with handtraps like the Bystial cards, Ishizu cards, and Herald of Orange Light. 

This deck easily accesses boss monsters capable of cracking boards and punching over monsters like Baronne, Chengying, Zeus, Accesscode and Underworld Goddess. Kashtira Fenrir is an absolute powerhouse when it comes to breaking boards, and it can be easily accessed from the GY with any Vernusylph card given it was milled earlier. 

If your deck was milled by your opponent, it will help you out on the crack-back during your turn, since a decent GY set-up enables more plays, resources and interruptions for the Naturia player. Every Naturia Sacred Tree milled represents an additional monster on your field to use as Synchro/Link/XYZ material for the OTK!

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

GENERAL TIPS

 

  • Before milling with Kelbek and Agido, try to make and activate Abyss Dweller first so that your opponent doesn't plus with your mills.
  • Remember that using Vernusylph cards EARTH-LOCK YOUR MONSTER EFFECTS FOR THE REST OF THE TURN! Try to use your non-earth effects before using a Vernusylph card. I personally did this misplay several times, often costing me the game, try not to be like me lol
  • Try to set up Gravekeeper's Trap as soon as possible. It searches every Earth Fairy in your deck, including the Vernusylph cards! Also, if you have drawn Naturia Sacred Tree, you can discard it with Gravekeeper's Trap to search for both an Earth Fairy and a Naturia card.
  • If your opponent has locked down the field with a crazy monster floodgate like Bagooska or an unkillable tower like I:P boosted Avramax, use Underworld Goddess! This deck can create Ms. Underworld very easily since it readily spams the field with so many monsters like no tomorrow with the Naturia, Vernusylph and Ishizu cards working together. 
  • If you make Chengying, its effect to banish your opponent's card in their field and GY can be triggered as a quick effect by the Ishizu cards Mudora and Keldo, as well with the Bystial cards. 
  • If you use I:P Masqurena + Bystial Druiswyrm on your opponent's turn to make Knightmare Unicorn, you can remove two cards at once (one targeted shuffle, 1 targeted/send of monster). 
  • If you get interrupted too much and you're in a bad position, make Bagooska to stall for resources. 
  • The most interchangeable cards in the deck are the Bystial cards (when you're not facing a light/dark deck) and the herald cards (Diviner and Orange Light). If you wanna cut the deck to make it more compact, you can take out these 10 cards to make this deck a 45 card deck. 
  • Decks that counter Tearlaments are usually also bad match-ups for this deck - like Floowandereeze and Dracoslayers (the variant that turbos out Necrovalley). Be sure to side appropriately for those match-ups. 

 

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

 

I'll be honest, when I watched the two most recent YCS this "Tear Zero" format, I wanted to take a break playing competitively for a while. Everything felt overwhelming, boring, similar and crazy. Our favourite decks that we piloted were decimated and thrown aside by the unstoppable mermaid juggernaut. Let's not forget the back-to-back chain link 10s in Tear mirror matches (Pak vs. Hani feature match anyone?)! While it's enjoyable for some duelists, I can say with confidence that a 1 deck format with mind-numblingly long turns and chains is not for me.

However, when I discovered Naturia Ishizu, it offered to me a breath of fresh air I needed from the stale competitive match-ups, and hooooo boy is it fun to play and pilot! It's perfectly unique, competitive and interesting all at once while being able to play toe-to-toe with the strongest decks of the format. The immense synergy of Naturia, Ishizu and Vernusylph creating this Earth-attribute symphony is just so incredible!

I'll try out my luck with these cute bugs, flowers and eldritch horrors at my Locals, and hopefully it reinvigorates my passion for competitive Yugioh in this "Tear Zero" format. 


GLHF Duelists!
Something I slapped together as a first deck I wanted to show my friends to see if I should buy it

deck_excerpt: UCT on a budget for my broke bois
deck_description:
Just a budget deck I've been having fun with. You could easily make the deck even cheaper (like say replacing pot of prosperity with pot of duality or something).

Extra Deck Cards (that didn't make it for budget reasons):
1x Spright Elf
1x Borreload Dragon
1x Borreload Savage Dragon
1x PSY-Framelord Omega

Side Deck (also not included for budget reasons): 
1x Evolzar Dolkka
1x Evilswarm Exciton Knight
1x Knightmare Unicorn
1x I:P Masquerena
2x Effect Veiler
1x Visas Starfrost
3x Dark Ruler No More
1x Twin Twisters
2x Cosmic Cyclone
2x Evenly Matched

2 easy combos:
1. Oviraptor (easily searchable with fossil dig) search Miscellaneousauras to hand, activate Misc. effect to protect your dinos while you setup, then banish Misc. for Archosaur to get a Pill. Archosaur can then be turned into a Linkuriboh (which you could summon Pentestag or something with, banish Linkuriboh and a dino of ur choice to get UCT and go for an OTK).
2. If you have Lost World out you can summon a token, then attack it and use Lost World's effect to save the token and bounce either a Babycerasauras or Petiterandon to the graveyard to get a free monster out (and still kill the token if you want).
3. Use literally any XYZ to battle and then dump Zeus on the board to nuke it.

deck_name: Tier 0 Ishizu Tearlaments Deck 3 Nov 2022 - 13 Feb 2023

deck_description:
Deck by Rlyhightimes.

"Dinomorphia has one glaring weakness, paying lifepoints. even with some pretty busted effects, continually paying half your lifepoints puts you in a bad position when it comes to the timeclock. If a game is forced to time, you are basically guarenteed a loss because your lifepoints will always be lower at the end of whatever phase the game might be in outside of maybe your battle phase.

That being said. the name of the game is move fast. Shutdown your opponent in the first turn and push for game as soon as possible. going second is a challenge for this deck but not undoable. and when you do know your going second, the evenly matched cleans up nicely 

My favorite play is to prioritize getting at least 2 level 4's on the field at the start of your turn 2 using alert in the opponents end phase. xyz into raider's knight and raider's knight into Arc Rebellion. with usually at least a rextrum or two kentregina's on the field, Arc Rebellion gets HUGE and can swing over any attack position for game. Warning Point helps with this if you catch your opponents off guard when they summon something in attack position looking to use it for a special summon.

-AA ZEUS is a nice followup with all the xyz access this deck provides.

*Its important to note you should prioritize getting sonic in the grave as soon as possible or fusing off from the field to mitigate battle damage as Diplos/Therizia are easy targets to swing over if you have been paying lots of life.

-Recovering with this deck is sometimes hard because you dedicate all the gas in early game. Sometimes its best to scoop and get into the side deck if they shut down your board as it will be a race against time to secure game 3 and you can side in more effective traps for whatever matchup you face 

All in all I think this decks weakness is itself when it comes to competitive play. between the OP effects (like a walking skill drain in rex) and multitude of negates, winning isnt usually the issue. I find myself going to time more often then i like and getting handed a loss even when i have complete control of the board. Definatly my favorite rogue deck by far.

There is absolutely nothing better than pissing off meta decks playing a bunch of traps" -Rlyhightimes
2 Aluber because only got the third after the tournament

The tagline is not a typo.

Feedback is always welcome!

deck_excerpt: yosenju, anti-meta, zeus, gagaga cowboy, funny build
deck_description:
This is a sample version of a yosenju trap with a (somewhat) modern build.

I suggest you to adjust the side deck, i'm giving options of engines that you can choose. You can use any kaijus, Triple Tactics Talent, some hand traps, backrow removal, anything you like, as long as it isn't something that will lock YOU out.

If you don't wanna play Dogmatika, you'll have free slots on 4 cards in the extra deck. ( Paleozoic Cambroraster, PSY-Framelord Omega, Garura, and N'tss )

The good thing in this deck is that you can use most floodgates, for example: Lose 1 Turn, Rivalry of Warlords, Gozen Match.

Skill Drain is a real problem, like any other monster negate. You can run spell/trap removal like Cosmic Cyclone, Heavy Storm Duster, Harpie's Feather Duster.

At the start of your turn you will mostly have only set cards, except when any Yosenju effect is negated at the end phase or if you already activated Tenki. Knowing this fact, it is really interesting to play Lightning Storm... as many as you can afford!!

The thing about this deck is that you can pass with no monsters on your side of the field, make that into your advantage. You can do a godly removal with Drowning Mirror Force or even do double bounces with Yosenjus' Sword Sting. Those are the two obvious picks for this deck, but make sure they will stay until the best moment to utilise them, that's when you'll need to have Lord of the Heavenly Prison revealed in your hand, protecting these cards of being destroyed. 

As the new december 2022 banlist releases, now you can play up to 3 copies of Dimensional Fissure or even use 3 of Macro Cosmos, you can use what you prefer. Banning your own spell/traps won't make a difference, but personally a continuous spell is more convenient to me, even if it banishes only monsters (including pendulum scales).

Talking about graveyard control, you could even side Necrovalley, it will lock the Ishizu shufflers and Tearlaments fusion effects. It covers most weak points that Abyss Dweller doesn't affect, such as Spright Elf! 

The ratio of Yosenju Izna and Yosenju Tsujik, is pretty much variable based of consistency or purely metacall, to ensure they won't imperm you during the normal summon string. Now that you can play with 3 copies of Fire Formation - Tenki, the third Yosenju Izna is not that much important to hold the deck consistency, as you can add it with Fire Formation - Tenki anyways.

I also have a similar build that I made on Master Duel, keep in mind that the video is not avaliable in English, but you can still get the decklist as an example of Yosenju Trap.

deck_excerpt: Luck coin and dice and stuff
I can finally play naturia! YAY!
deck_description:
The deck basically uses the Vernusylph and Exchange of the Spirit archetypes to help bolster the Naturia cards with rank 4 support and constituency boosting.

Firstly Naturias the stars are the new cards mole cricket and camellia. Basically you either get cricket out by sending tree to graveyard via foolish burial goods, Mudora setting gravekeper's trap to discard a sacred tree bricking your hand, or curious on a follow up play. One for one also works for this if you draw into it. Once you get cricket on board you tribute it with its effect to special camellia which let's you send sacred tree (the graveyard effect of tree is not once per turn) to search naturia blessing which you will use to redice cricket and syncro naturia beast. Then the other effect of cricket will trigger letting you revive cricket, and from there you can keep him on board for the opponents turn or you can link him off for linkuribo since cricket will revive himself once an opponent summons from the extra deck. 

That's the basic combo from there the idea is on opponents turn once cricket is revived you can use his tribute effect again to grab an appropriate naturia for the situation (vein for s/t negate, sunflower for monster, stinkbug to skip battle ect.). 

That's the basics of the naturia's so for verns and ishizus basically they are ment to support but they have there own quirks. Starting with verns they help bridge the naturia and ishizu cards since the discard and revival effect works for both archetypes and the help the ishizu cards with the discard requirements. Awakening forest helps by sending a earth to grave which while letting you not commit your normal summon also sets up ishizu plays or let you mill to potentially hit tree. Flourishing hills is an extender to let you get to misting seedlings which let's you search any ishizu or vern off of the discard effect. Thawing mountains is the least impactful since it is neither a level 4 or the most impactful for the effect it can potentially let you draw into a starter if you brick opening. 

Ok to cover the ishizu/exchange of the Spirit cards. The reason I'm not running full of each is simple this deck is built with some future proofing in mind namely it is to reflect how the ocg has the archetype with keldo and agido at limited, and while the tcg banlist doesn't mirror the ocg I'd rather adjust to the hit sooner than later. Firstly mudora who I feel does most in this deck he can special himself from hand by pitching a earth fairy and doing so sets gravekeepers trap from deck which either let's you unbrick a hand with sacred tree in it for beast combo while getting and ishizu monster to hand for an easy rank 4 or a kelbez/keldo for the opponents turn. Mudora and keldo also have nice synergy with the deck since they can banish themselves to shuffle 3 cards back into the deck as a quick effect (5 if you run exchange of the Spirit and its in the gy.), and this let's you either interrupt an opponents play if there deck relays on cards staying in the gy for effects, or to shuffle your own naturia cards back into the deck for follow up namely sacred tree, camellia, naturia blessing. 

Typically depending on your hand you should be able to make beast and possibly a rank 4 so the deck has rank 4 options to make use of it bagooska and Dweller are fairly straight forward they help with locking down the opponents so you can follow up on your turn, cowboy is ment for a more competitive setting to help win a tie, and redoer is the most iffy rank 4 but he generally will be annoying to get rid of and can steal opponents cards off there deck/give advantage if they hit a spell, and zeus us pretty straight forward of a board is in the opponents favor attack with any of the xyzs and then clean up with zeus or hold it and make the opponent commit. 

The syncros are not as pronounced as some other lists I've seen but I talked with some mutual players and they thought that to many if the high lv syncros aren't really achievable unless you luck into a good hand that has an extra blessing to use to syncro on the opponents turn. With that in mind barkion and beast are pretty straight forward they are great in and out of archetype for s/t negate. Chengyang admittedly has the extra blessing scenario in mind but even if you make it on your turn chenyang has a interesting interaction with keldo and mudora since they banish themselves to shuffle other cards that means you can control when you can use Chengyangs banish to a degree which I find to be a fun interaction on top of it being generally good and the level isn't much of an issue to go into. Psychic end punisher is generally a good back up boss if just need something that's hard to get rid of with a good statline.

Lastly the links i:p let's you get into unicorn on the opponents turn to interrupt and your likely to see this since cricket in grave can bring itself back if you don't already have the other material on board, and same idea for cerberus for monster removal. Curious is well a curious pick for the deck but the main deck is all earth and runs 3 different types between the naturias and the other 2, and anything in the extra deck that us earth is also an extra type, and the idea is as a follow up play if we have a somewhat depleted board we assemble curious to send tree and we can either blessing back a cricket for 2 potential material which will be enough to make borrelsword dragon. Borrelsword is nice and can help close a game but in all honesty accesscode talker is a better for for the combo since you can just link anything with curious for accesscode, but this deck is ment to be more budget friendly and I personally do not like how accesscode is the easy answer for a boss monster for a deck.

I'll quickly cover the side deck basically it's to help for first turn plays depending on what I'm facing, pankertops is a staple going second and he's another small world bridge into cricket, vein is ment to replace sunflower against s/t focused decks, same for cosmic Cyclone and harpies either duster, evenly matched makes a good board breaker to a going first opponent that over extends opening up, and gozen match isn't perfect but since the entire main deck is earth it works just fine and anti spell turns off decks that have alot of s/t reliance/ openers.

I'm happy a deck that was a meme is in a usable spot its not meta or the best, but I hope to find some success with a deck I just like.

deck_name: Cheaply Craft Witch Crafters for Under Dog Format!
deck_description:
Budget Witchcrafters revolves around getting out Fusions with reoccurring Spells from the grave to support Spellcasters on the field.

As long as you have a way to get both a spellcaster and Confusion confession either in the grave or in the hand by the end of the turn, you can easily get towards Witchcrafter Vice-Madame or Quintet Magician on your current or next turn, after that, it's more casual Witchcrafter things, using Magicians' Souls to get Either hand based on the situation or activating Secret Village of the Spellcasters to stall until your next turn.

Finally, we have Links to use thanks to Witchcrafter Vice-Madame's effect to special summon out more Witchcrafters from the Grave and use them to summon a charmer and link climb to Unicorn/Apollo.

deck_name: why? easter deck bunnies?Sacred Sheep Tree, Baromet,Promotional Card

deck_description:
A decks who's entire design philosophy and game plan is based around 1500 defence spellcasters from multiple different archetypes to create a power and varied combo deck with an incredibility unpredictable game plan. The main representative archetypes found in this deck is the charmers acting as the main glue and enforcer of the 1500 defence spellcaster play style, Magistus and Dogmatika with some lesser repersentation from swordsoul and Gravekeeper's.

The Play style can go in two directions based on your opening hands and opponent. The first is attempt to resolve Awakening of the Possessed - Nefariouser Archfiend and go for a link 2, this triggers Archfiends effect to search when it goes to the gy and adds you a possessed spell or trap. Doing this with I:P as the end board target will grant you at least 2 points of disruption on your opponent if we ignore any extra parts of your end board. The other end board options are going for the synchros, namely Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity and locking your opponent out of activating effects based on what is equipped to Zoroa and then backing him up with the charmer/possessed spell and trap line, the Dogmatika members though it is very possible and consistent to end on both Zoroa, the Magistus Conflagrant Calamity and a link 2 in the same turn if you open with the right cards.

One of the free agent cards is Gravekeeper's shaman. What you do is send Gravekeeper's shaman off of magicians souls and then summon the souls (you can make this more consistent by adding more illusions/Rites). From there summon any level 4 or lower earth monster, in this case we have every nefarious eater of nefariousness, Familiar possessed - Aussa and the Magistus of Grimoire Crowley who can change his attribute and then send the souls and the traptrix to the gy and that will let you summon awakening of the possessed nefariouser archfiend from the deck who's effect is monster reborn on any level 4 or lower so bring back a monster and then link summon away awakening of the possessed nefariouser archfiend and another monster which will then trigger archfiends search effect which will add Possessed partnership, a trap that can summon any 1500 def spellcaster from hand or gy and if you control 2 or more face-up monsters with a different attribute, it becomes non targeting face-up removal as well. This can also be used to summon both Eccelsia, Zoroa, etc who is also in this deck. So what you get is a consistency engine from magicians souls with doubles as both extenders and draw power, A blanket negate all activated monster effects in the gy on a passive effect from gravekeeper's shaman and a powerful removal trap that doesn't target and can be used to summon other cards if needed. This combo is very strong against any deck the uses a lot of monster effects in the gy. This namely includes Tearlament which when timed right (likely after a large mill or they've normal summoned) can end the Tearlaments player's entire game.

Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous's use is more simple since she is both an extender and a soft super poly enabler by summoning Fallen of Albaz from the hand or deck, making her an amazing surprise option and double removal that can potnetially not eat up your normal going 2nd and removal 2 monsters at once if Ecclesia is summoned using possessed partnership. Incredible Ecclesia also lets the deck run the Albaz fusion monster line up which is very strong as a whole and gives the deck more options and even lets you summon or search Dogmatika monsters by sending titaniklad the ash dragon off of the effect of mirrorjade the iceblade dragon after summoning it by using an oppenets extra deck monster.

Overall the deck is a lot more powerful then it let's on and makes the best use of all the 1500 defence spellcasters has released over the years and the support that Konami released with the Charmers structure deck to make a deck with tons of options, adaptability and tech options that can take on even the strongest of meta decks thanks to how powerful it’s lock down can potentially can be and it will only get better as Konami releases more spellcaster themes and cards with the prized 1500 def stat line.

Cyber Dragon Deck, still confused on how it works 50% of the time

The Magical Muskets have been some of my favorite cards for awhile now, they have a cool aesthetic and have a huge amount of flexibility when it comes to how they can control the game. Literally any strategy that uses a spell or trap card can start to build advantage with these cards. The extra cards do add up, overwhelming your opponent until they have nothing left. Unfortunately their ceiling was unjustifiably capped, they weren't xenophobic but with no modern, generic, fiend support they had no true way of recovering if your opponent could overwhelm your interactions...

But um these Labrynth cards are like really good. They have an actual win condition and are pretty consistent in achieving said condition. Beyond being good, they provide generic fiend support... and they mainly run through trap cards... you see where I'm going with this?

Beyond the already amazing Labrynth, the new ~Muckraker From the Underworld adds a huge amount of flexibility and recovery to the deck. With it we can use a Tour Guide to get into a Musket names and get off to the races.

I was having a lot of fun with this concept, it was very powerful, very flexible and very fun. Playing it made me feel blissful almost serene in a way. And then I had an idea that damned this deck to hell. Because we have quite a few ways in engine to trigger a Kelbek or Agido... and the recovery of these cards are pretty insane between cards like ~Big Welcome Labrynth or ~Labrynth Set-Up and ~Magical Musketeer Wild or ~Magical Musketeer Doc... so if we were to oh I don't know discard a copy of Keblek off a Muckraker and mill 5 cards... we'd essentially have a second hand to work with in theory.

This story is why I bring my sins before you. I tried to make it cool by adding in a little artifact package to add more fairy names and keeping in line with the trap theme. :)

deck_description: A classic aqua control deck made of N/R cards for the Novakin Monthly tournament

A deck that I'm surprised isn't on YouTube: Fossil Ishizu. Yes, Fossil Tear is an overhwlemingly stronger deck, but Fossils are just as fond of having their monsters sent to the Graveyard by card effect. This deck was named after one of the most famous fossil specimens in America: Sue, one of the largest and most complete Tyrannosaurus Rex skeletons.

 

Strategy-wise, this deck still prefers to go second, especially due to the 9 hand traps, 2 copies of Lightning Storm and 1 Harpies' Feather Duster. However, the Level 4 EARTH Fairies all provide you with 2 options for Rank 4s. Minerva the Exalted Lightsworn can mill 3 cards for potential Graveyard setup, and Bagooska can be summoned in Defense Position as a potential floodgate. This means if you need to go first, you can sit on Bagooska to lock your opponent's monster effects down for a turn or two. 

 

One of the best cards in the deck is Aussa the Earth Channeler. She can discard herself and another EARTH monster to search an EARTH monster with 1850 or less ATK. If the other monster that got discarded was Agido or Kelbek, you can then activate their Graveyard effects to mill 5 cards. If you use Aussa's search effect, you can't activate the effects of non-EARTH monsters for the turn, which means you won't be able to use either of Minerva's effects. 

 

And your best normal summon for this deck is Mathematician, since he can mill a Level 4 or lower monster upon Normal Summon. This means you can mill Weathering Soldier to search Fossil Fusion or a card that mentions it, Shell Knight to search Gaia Plate the Earth Giant, or Agido/Kelbek to mill 5 cards. The best part is that Mathematician has less than 1850 ATK and is an EARTH monster, which means that Aussa the Earth Channeler can search him.

Summary

Mission Statement: Get Vice-Madame on the field ASAP.

Once she is on the field she can be the starter for the regular witchcrafter plays.

Cartesia is the way we access Madame. Need to see her in the opening so theres many ways of getting to her with Small World, Pot of Extravagance and Branded in High Spirits.

Optimal opener is probably Cartesia + Schmietta + Creation + any other witchcrafter spell. Ends on Vice Master, Verre, Bystreet, Golem Aruru in hand with an incoming Haine on your opponents turn.

Kinda need to go first because this deck cannot play through negates 9 out of 10 times.

Deck Breakdown

Main Deck

1x Witchcrafter Golem Aruru: Good card, uncommon piece of interaction that many decks aren't prepared for, no need to have more than 1.

1x Witchcrafter Madame Verre: The "boss" of the deck, almost every game the aim is to sit on this card, 1 copy is all you need.

1x Witchcrafter Haine: Solid card, secondary summon to Verre.

1x Witchcrafter Edel: Decent card, there are times when you open a big Witchcrafter and cartesia so having Vice-Madam summon Edel to reborn them comes up often enough to include her.

3x Witchcrafter Schmietta: Best small witchcrafter, easy 3 of.

3x Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous: The way to Vice-Madam, need to see her as often as possible.

1x Witchcrafter Pittore: Not very good, mainly used for the witchcrafter name but grave effect can be useful in some turn 1s.

1x Witchcrafter Potterie: Worst small witchcrafter, if Vice-Madame is on your field your hand probably won't be empty. Only played for more names for small world and Vice-Madame.

3x Witchcrafter Genni: Close second to Schmietta, another easy 3 of.

1x Witchcrafter Bystreet: Pretty decent card, mostly searched by Schmietta so one copy is fine.

1x Witchcrafter Scroll: Bad card, played for the Witchcrafter name.

1x Instant Fusion: Pretty good in this deck, Restrict can be used as a hand trap negate or as fodder for Vice-Master. If your hand is really bad you can just discard it for one of the small witchcrafter's cost.

3x Pot of Extravagance: Digger for cards, preferred over desires because of the many one of's in the main deck.

1x Ready Fusion: Fodder for Vice-Master or discard material. Could maybe be increased depending on consistency of getting to Vice-Madame.

1x Reasoning: Mills for witchcrafter spells and traps and put up and extra body which this deck can struggle at doing.

3x Small World: A way to get to Cartesia or any other monster if your hands good enough, everyone's a spellcaster.

1x Witchcrafter Collaboration: Bad card, only played for the Witchcrafter name.

1x Witchcrafter Confusion Confession: Bad card, look at Branded Fusion, only played for the Witchcrafter name.

3x Witchcrafter Creation: Good card, searches all your Witchcrafters. Either used to get the Schmietta to hand or to search Golem and trigger Vice-Madame.

3x Witchcrafter Holiday: Pretty decent card, playing 3 helps the stickiness of the big Witchcrafters.

1x Branded in High Spirits: Good card, used to search the Cartesia.

2x Chaos Scepter Blast: Really good piece of removal, probably the most cut-able card if you want more defensive options from hand traps.

1x Witchcrafter Draping: Bad card, only used for the Witchcrafter name.

1x Witchcrafter Unveiling: Bad card only used for the Witchcrafter name.

1x Witchcrafter Patronus: Okay card, searches your spells and recycles your banished monsters. Searchable with a Schmietta dump and Vice-Master add. Better used to add banished spells from Genni's effect to hand.

Extra Deck

3 copies of the important ones because of the Extravagance. If you opt for Desires instead then you'll have more space here but Witchcrafters tend not to use the extra deck that much anyway.

3x Master of Chaos: Branded in High Spirits target.

3x Witchcrafter Vice-Madame: The actual boss of the deck, does a lot in speeding up the usual Witchcrafter plays while adding a little more power.

3x Sanwich: Ready fusion target. If you increase ready fusion in the main deck then add more targets here, swap out the link monsters.

3x Milenium eyes Restrict: Instant fusion target, monster effect negate or fodder for Vice-Madame.

1x Black luster Soldier - Soldier of Chaos: Can sometimes come up in a more drawn out game where you need a sticky monster. You can revive back your Verre/Haine that you used to make this.

1x Underworld Goddess of the Closed World: Vice-Madame can rack up a lot of monsters on field quickly, use them to go into this if your opponent sits on any hard to remove monsters.

1x Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians: Revive your spellcasters.

Side Deck

These are some options that you might see in a regular Witchcrafter list or just some good tech options.

Magicalized Fusion: Prefered Cartesia as the way to Vice-Master because she can be searched easier than Magicalized Fusion.

Secret Village of the Spellcasters: Stops your opponent from activiating spells but then the only way to trigger Vice-Madame is your own monsters, limiting your timing options. Also always the potential of locking yourself.

Magician Souls: Really only helps in later turns with card advantage and there was enough spellcaster fodder for Vice-Madame.

Chaos Scepter Blast: Like I said in the main deck part, a really good removal option so if you want one more then knock yourself out.

Spell Chronicle Package: Banishing 5 Witchcrafter spells then drawing them off Patronus feels really broken, but it's too slow and with Vice-Master recycling even just 1 or 2 Witchcrafter spells is really easy now. Without Spell Chronicle, I also cut Foolish Burial Goods and Metalfoes Fusion. The draw 1 or dump a Witchcrafter spell/trap just wasn't worth including. 3rd best package here.

Magician's Restage Package: This package was cut half for lack of space and half for lack of good ways to get Restage into the grave. Without Foolish Burial Goods and Magician Souls you are left with Reasoning and discarding for the small Witchcrafters cost and opening hand space is already tight. To me this is the second best package to put into the main deck from these side deck options.

Defensive Package: Called by, Crossout and Handtraps. This deck loses, hard, to ash or a monster negate on Cartesia. If your wanting a slightly more competitive version then swap in these cards. I'd take out the offensive Chaos Scepter Blast and go over the 40 cards but you can mess about with the ratios that you like best. The best package from here to improve the deck list.

Optimal Combo

Thought I'd layout the combo with the "best" hand I mentioned above.

Normal Cartesia

Cartesia Effect to Fusion Vice-Madame using herself and Schmietta.

Activate Creation, chain Vice-Madame to special a Witchcrafter

Summon a small witchcrafter, search Golem Aruru

Schmietta effect in grave, Chain Vice-Madame to add Creation back to hand.

Schmietta dump Bystreet or Holiday (if you have Bystreet in hand)

Small Witchcrafter effect, discarding your other Witchcrafter spell

Special Witchcrafter Madame Verre

End Phase, add spells back to hand/spell trap zone

End board should be Vice-Madame, Verre, Bystreet + 2 Witchcrafter spells and Golem Aruru in hand with 1 other card that you opened. On your opponents turn, Vice-Madame specials a small witchcrafter who specials into Haine, chaining Vice-Madame to either add the discarded spell or pop a card.

End.

Might not be a perfect list as there is still a little more work to put into it, mess around with it so it fits your style better.

deck_name: Ishizu, Judge of the Burning Abyss
deck_description:
By far one of the worst decks to combine with the Ishizu engine, but that's only because the Level 3 BAs are some of the most xenophobic monsters in Yu-Gi-Oh. 

 

Anyways, this deck can do well going first, but it's equally suited to go second, due to the 3 Forbidden Droplets and 6 hand traps. Ideally, your first turn-board consists of either Beatrice or Bagooska. Bagooska can potentially stop your opponent's monster effects for a turn, while Beatrice can mill an Agido or Kelbek, which is essentially like dropping a nuke on your opponent's turn thanks to the BAs' effects when sent to the Graveyard.
My current take on infernoid, I'm still working on it though but this works pretty well.

deck_excerpt: An updated go second list for Cyber Dragon for the OCG Format.
deck_description:
An updated list from https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/cyber-dragon-307587

Summary

Main game plan is to break through pesky boards and OTK (depending on the match up). If need be, the deck can board out to be more control-oriented using flood gates like Rivalry of Warlords, Dimensional Barrier and Cybernetic Overflow.

The cyberdark package allows the deck to deal up to 19100 damage in a turn from 1 Cyber Dragon Core + Any Spell or Trap + Any Monster if uninterrupted
(Note: Cyberdark Chimera + Power Bond needs to be in the deck to work. You can consider running a bigger package of 2x Cyberdark Claw, 1x Cyberdark Chimera, 2x Power Bond, 1x Cyberdark Realm, 1x Cybernetic Horizon for better consistency)

Normal Core -> Activate Realm -> Add Chimera -> Normal Chimera using Realm -> Link Sieger with Core + Chimera -> Power Bond fusing Sieger + Core to Rampage -> Activate Rampage to dump Nachster + Herz -> Activate Herz to add Nachster -> Activate Nachster to pitch any Monster to Special Summon -> Activate Nachster to Special Sieger

You could also use Nachster to bring out regular Cyber Dragon if it is in the GY to summon Infinity

Synergies

Clockwork Night + Any Cyber Dragon = Field Nuke
Clockwork Night as a discard target for Cyberdark Chimera to search Therion "King" Regulus
Therion "King" Regulus to equip Herz to add a Cyber Dragon later in the turn when Regulus leaves the field
Therion "King" Regulus to equip Cyber Dragon that can be used as material for Chimeratech Fortress Dragon since fortress only required a named Cyber Dragon to be on the field
Galaxy Soldier + Herz = Infinity
Invoked Mechaba can be a target for Cyber Dragon Nachster and Cyber Dragon Nova (floating effect)
Jizukiru, searchable by Repair Plant + Relinquished Anima

If the budget allows, consider running Pot of Prosperity, Forbidden Droplet, AA-Zeus.
Other options include Machine Duplication, Therion Discolosseum

deck_excerpt: A Generaider deck inspired by the best game in 2022: God of War Ragnarok!
deck_description:
Not gonna lie, I was never really interested in the Generaider archetype. But Vara and Laevateinn, its two newest support cards, were introduced in the same year as God of War: Ragnarok. The name is appropriate Generaider's monsters are named after figures in Norse mythology. I've been a fan of God of War for years, and I recently watched all of the cutscenes in the storyline. No spoilers, but God of War: Ragnarok is the end of the Norse saga, so the next game will more than likely involve another pantheon.

 

Aaaaaanyway, this is a go-first deck, although with 9 hand traps, you aren't doomed if you have to go second. Your goal is to get Generaider Boss Stage out to set up your board, and Laevateinn works as good removal and interruptions for the archetype.

King Ramseeeeeees! The man in gauze, the man in gauze! -Courage the Cowardly Dog

 

While everybody and their mama was playing Ishizu Tearlaments, I decided to think outside the box. So that's when I got the idea to play Ishizu Zombie World. It made sense--Kelbek and Agido both mill 5 to 10 cards when sent from the hand or Deck to the Graveyard, and Zombies are just like 7th graders who listen to Linkin Park: they want to be in the Graveyard. 

 

This deck can do well going first or second, due to Zombie World's inherit go-first strategy and this deck's 6 hand traps, 3 Forbidden Droplets, and 3 Super Polymerization!  However, due to the presence of the Ishizu engine, the Extra Deck has more Rank 4 monsters than Synchros.

deck_excerpt: A Deck For Fellow Dark Magician Fans Who Refuse To Give Up Hope
deck_description:
So basically, this is a deck that I theroized about after seeing one simular on this site before. The whole idea is to find fast ways to get your main cards (Dark magician and chaos monsters) on the field to tap into your extra deck, to cut off your opponents support lines. 

THE HOPEFUL WAY THAT IT WORKS: 

A starting hand of spells and traps that allow you to get dark magicians out of your deck and onto the field ASAP. A good combination to have is having Secret Village of The Spellcasters with any of your spellcaster monsters (i.e. Dark Magician) on the field to stop your opponent from using spells. (Credits to HypeUp for the card idea). ((Use with risk of losing monsters and not being able to use spell cards). After your dark magicians are on the field, you can either start linking summoning to build up to someone like Black Luster Soldier-Soldier of Chaos or Underworld Godess of the Closed World. Added in for some extra umph and support is Ebon Illusion and Ebon High magician if your into XYZ, and some generally powerful fusion cards. Once beatstick negate cards are on the field,  take control of the board and take the win. 

EXTRA GOODIES JUST IN CASE:

In case the deck bricks and you get a poor starting hand, I added 1 Magikuriboh to get Dark Magician back onto the field, and a personal favorite spell card of mine, Piercing The Darkness. The idea is if you can't really get into your extra deck, to have eternal soul on the field combined with your Dork Magicians. That way, you can at least  hope to out muscle your opponent while waiting for the opprotunity to get back into your extra deck. 

Thanks for using this deck if your interested, let me know what you think or if I should go back and revise anything! -D1pyy

deck_excerpt: Summon all the signer dragons in 1 turn (using ancient pixie as an ancient fairy substitute)
deck_description:
Ok, so this deck's goal is pretty simple. Summon all the signer dragons turn 1. Also, I put in a bunch of upgrades to the dragon, just in case you don't get the combo pieces, and synchron explorer for follow-up plays. You may switch out Synchron explorer, Life Stream dragon, Power tool braver dragon, (if you do, switch out Moon mirror shield) shooting star dragon, Accel synchron, Starlight Junction, Hot red dragon Archfiend abyss, Or phantasmal lord for any card(s) you wish.  Also, if you want, you may switch out scarlight red dragon archfiend for red dragon archfiend/ hot red dragon archfiend, blackfeather darkrage for black-winged dragon, or black rose moonlit dragon for black rose dragon, I just found them more useful in most situations. Here's the combo


Junk converter and any tuner+ any of the level 2s I put in the deck+ - All signer dragons.

First, your gonna wanna use junk converter to add junk synchron from the deck to hand, then normal summon it and use it's effect to special summon Junk converter from the graveyard. If you have Synchron carrier, normal summon that first. If you have caligo crow or Doppel warrior, special summon them. next, synchro summon junk speeder using junk synchron and the level 2 you special summoned In your extra monster zone, and special summon Stardust synchron, junk synchron, and assault synchron. Use Stardust Synchron's effect to add Stardust illumination from your deck to your hand, then use it to send stardust tail from your deck to your graveyard. next use assault warrior and junk speeder to synchro summon Black rose dragon, then use jet synchron to synchro summon black-winged Dragon using itself and Black rose dragon, in your extra monster zone. use jet Synchron's effect to add junk servant to your hand, then special summon it. Use stardust synchron and junk servant to synchro summon scarlight red dragon archfiend. Use stardust Synchron's effect to tribute scarlight red dragon archfiend and special summon itself. use assault warrior to special summon it back to the field and use stardust tail to special summon itself. use stardust synchron and stardust tail to synchro summon stardust dragon and use the stardust tails effect to special summon a token. Use junk converter and Junk synchron to summon Dark Dimension Soldier. Then use junk converters effect to special summon Junk synchron back from the graveyard. Activate Stardust illumination in your grave to banish it and increase the tokens level by one. Then use the token and Junk synchron to Synchro summon Garden Rose maiden. Use dark dimension's effect to special summon assault synchron from your banish zone, then use it to synchro summon Power tool dragon. Use power tool dragons effect to search Fleuret de fluer. Activate Fleuret to special summon assault synchron from your graveyard, then use that and garden rose maiden to synchro summon ancient pixie dragon. equip Fleuret to power tool. Then, use garden rose maidens effect to special summon black rose dragon from your graveyard,  therefore giving you all 6 signer dragons. IF you have junk servant in your hand at the start of the combo, do not use jet synchrons special ability to search it. instead, special summon it as normal, complete the combo up to before you use Living fossil, then use jet synchrons ability to special summon itself, use it to synchro summon Life Stream dragon using power tool dragon, then use Fleuret de fluer as normal and complete the combo. If you draw monster reborn, Living fossil. or Fleuret de fluer at the start of the combo, play the combo all the way until you add Fleuret from your deck to your hand,(if you already have it in your hand, add living fossil, if you already have living fossil, add Fleuret as normal) then use monster reborn/Living fossil to summon jet synchron from your graveyard, use it to synchro summon life force dragon, then proceed to finish the combo as normal. At the end of either combo, use black rose garden to +1 off of ancient pixie, plus pop 1 attack if it's the second turn, as well as weaken your opponents monsters on  next turn.

Junk Synchron + any lv 2 - 4 signer dragons

Synchro summon junk speeder, then special summon assault synchron, stardust synchron, junk synchron, and jet synchron. Use stardust synchron to search stardust illumination. activate the spell you searched to send stardust trail to the graveyard. Use assault synchron to synchro summon power tool dragon, then use it's effect to search living fossil. Then use jet synchron to synchro summon black-winged dragon or life stream dragon. search junk servant and special summon it. Use junk servant and stardust synchron to synchro summon scarlight red dragon archfiend tribute scarlight to summon Stardust synchron, then use stardust trail and assault synchron to summon scarlight and stardust trail from the grave. use stardust synchron and stardust trail to summon stardust dragon, then use stardust trail to summon a token. Banish stardust illumination to increase the tokens level by 1. then use both junk synchron and the token to synchro summon Dark dimension soldier. Use dark dimension soldier to summon assault synchron, then use assault synchron and dark dimension soldier to synchro-summon black rose or Ancient Pixie dragon. Instead, you could summon garden rose maiden,use living fossil to summon junk synchron, then use it and garden rose to summon black-winged dragon

IMPORTANT: If you draw stardust trail, everything is still ok. use the stardust illumination to send your second stardust synchron to the graveyard.

edit: Master Duel has the new support now!! I'm so happy! I love weather painters so much

Master Duel not having The Weather Forecast kinda sucks but the archetype still seems solid, as long as you can get your footing. Since extra deck plays are harder without The Weather Forecast, I thought it'd be good to use an engine that fills up the extra deck quite a bit, hence Ghostrick Utopic! It's still better to go into The Weather Painter Rainbow for negates, especially if you already have a lot of Weather Painters on board. The Engine is really useful regardless, mostly because you can get out Number F0: Utopic Draco Future without as much setup and it has better protection than anything else in here.

With these hand traps, Small World can always grab The Weather Painter Snow as far as I can tell. I'd recommend using Effect Veiler in place of Droll & Lock Bird but it's what I had :P Side deck has a few other good cards.

Enjoy!

Use the game YGOOmega test combo before the deck is updated in Yugioh Master Duel. Will update this deck soon after the game when the maintenance is completed. Below is the deck profile for everyone's reference.

deck_excerpt: Virtual World with Zombies and Despia with a sprinkle of Bamboo Sword
deck_description:
This deck is very complicated. As such, I cannot give you a good combo line a what you "need" to do guide. All I can give are suggestions to an absolutely crazy combo deck.

Suggestion 1: make Beatrice, Lady of the Eternal a priority to get to. She is the key to accessing both the Zombie and Branded engines. On your turn, mill Despian Tragedy, add Aluber the Jester of Despia, Normal Summon him, add Branded in Red. On your opponent's turn you can use Branded in Red to get Guardian Chimera. On your opponent's turn, durring their Draw Phase, send the missing Zombie piece (Necroworld Banshee or Doomking Balerdroch) to the GY (Banshee is a Quick Effect, Balerdroch Special Summons himself during the Standby Phase). You will have hopefully milled the other piece off of The Zombie Vampire or Immortal Dragon.

Suggestion 2: Go for Power Tool Braver Dragon before Virtual World Kyubi - Shenshen, and never have both on the field at the same time. If you do, you can't use Braver Dragon. Braver Dragon is also a free draw two, hence why in tight resource states it's invaluable.

Suggestion 3: Don't go for the Zombie side if Zombie World is in the GY. It's useless at that point.

Suggestion 4: You can make Baronne de Fleur using Aluber and other sufficient material.

Suggestion 5: You can make Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon off of Immortal Dragon and Stardust Charge Warrior.

Suggestion 6: Have fun!

This deck is only around $270 USD, but you can make the price about $60 USD by making the following changes:

  • Removing the Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and D.D. Crow sets.
  • Replacing Guardian Chimera with Despian Proskenion & Branded in Red with Branded Banishment (to keep the same effect, kind of).
  • Replacing Baronne de Fleur with Red-Eyes Zombie Dragon Lord 
  • Replace Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder with Virtual World Beast - Jiujiu (I know, I know, really not ideal).

Do what you prefer with the Side Deck.

deck_excerpt: A deck that has fused Buster Blader, Blue-Eyes White Dragon & Fallen of Albaz!
deck_description:
I find this deck to be pretty consistant at coming up with fusions or syncro's. Use Buster Whelp or trap tricks to get your prolonged. Use that effect to get Buster Dragon to the field. In really good situations you can use a combo move of Destruction sword fusion & your opponents material to get the Buster Blader fusion monster out. or use sage with eyes of blue to either search buster whelp or sack The Maiden with eyes of blue to spam out 2 Blue-eyes which opens up the option to go into Number 100 Numeron Dragon for a massive 9000 damage! We also have the Branded Fusion which allows you to use the aforementioned monsters to create powerful fusion dragons of the Albaz archtype. I find going for Bastard of Ashen Dragon by using Buster Blader or Blue-Eye Jet Dragon to help with getting some monsters in the grave & make a pretty strong turn one monster. It used to have Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King of Calamity in the Main but I moved it to the extra deck becuase it was just one of the cards that was relativley easy to summon if I start with Prolog & Chain Resonator, but it just isn't as versitile as the other extra deck cards. You can readd it if you want. I'm not living & dying with the XYZ monsters in the extra deck. They are nice in certain cercomstances but maybe aren't worth the 3 slots they use up.

 

Ultimately, I'm sure people could refine this deck even better because I am not very good at deck building. This deck is far from perfect but I genuenly enjoy playing with this deck.

I thought it would be a fun idea to have Sacred Beasts use the Branded stuff, so I came up with this deck. I would like some help with building this deck for the Tier 0 Format we are currently in, so feel free to come up with neat ideas that would help.

deck_excerpt: Wat da hell, I will send you to jesus.
deck_description:
I'm a novice deck builder but this is the deck I've created after playing it for a while. This deck has 5 starter pieces that also play into one another whilst being and having decent exstenders giving this deck a lot of synergy, you are primarily going for Exosister boss monsters due to the restrictions from martha and vadis however there are times when you do need magistus monsters, as each magistus monster can steal, negate, or destroy Extra Deck Monsters and spell/trap cards. The magistus boss monster isn't half bad either as it can be a big beat stick and shut down plays from extra deck cards based off the card that is attached to it. Alternative Boss monster for this deck are Quintet magician and Underworld goddess, as one is a board wipe and can't be destroyed by card effects while the other can negate and stall and tribute your opponent's monster, works really well with I:P as you can cause disruption during your opponent's turn. Honnorable mentions for disruptive/boss monsters are ruddy rose or Chengying as they can help out by puting use into Dimension shifter if you see him in your hand whilst having cards in your graveyard. Chengying is a good general card and ruddy rose can possibly give Dimension shifter more value as it does bannish all cards in both gys, it could also take advantge of having sauge de fleur or evil thorn.

 

Combo Plays:

Litterally everything can combo into eachother, just be mindful when using Martha or Vadis as they lock you into exosister for the turn, General combos are:

S.Summon Martha and xyz summon into kaspitell or mikails (your preference) add pax and elis for guareenteed magnifica or for extended plays

N.summon zoroa, S.Summon another 4* spellcaster from your hand Synchro summon your boss magistus monster or extenders/negates, OR xyz summon Kaspitell or Mikailis, Grab pax to get martha, or just get martha with kaspitell, Xyz summon your opposite option use effect to grab another extender for later, Xyz summon mikailis and Kaspitell into Magnifica.

 

With Rillionia, same thing as zoroa except you have to grab trimagistus

 

with summoner monk, same thing as Zoroa except you Have to have a spell card in your hand

 

However, summoning the alternative boss monsters is harder but can be a game changer in your duel.

For Ruddy rose and Chengying You have to have a normal summon open and have zoroa on the field or S.Summoned with Trimagistus or monk (who should be on the field already or is also S.Summoned by Trimagistus) then tribute Monk or another monster S.Summoned by Monk or Zoroa With Dimesion Shifter then, synchro into those monsters.

For Quintet Magician very rewarding to summon but it is the hardest to summon, and unless you can play and search or have magicalized fusion in your hand ready your going to have a hard time with this one. If you plan to use magicalized fusion I recomend playing 1-2 Keeper of dragon magic as he is a lv 4 and can search "fusion" or "Polymerization" but he is a Dragon which can ruin ur magistus plays. If playing without keeper you need Zoroa and/or Monk and/or Rillionia, a non-copy 4* spellcaster, trimagistus, and a throw away spell card. there are exceptions depending on your hand variation which I will go over.

if you Don't have zoroa:

Activate trimagistus, S.Summon Rillionia or Monk and nomral summon the other, use both effect to grab fusion spell card and Zoroa, use Zoroa effect to equip artemis, S.Summon 4*star W/ zoroa effect, use artemis to grab crowley, then Fusion Summon.

if you Don't have Rillionia:

Samething as before just switching places with Rillionia and Zoroa.

if you Don't have monk, you must have 2 4* spellcasters or 1 and a Pax instead of a throw away spell:

activate Trimagistus, S.summon Rillionia or zoroa normal summon the other, equip artemis, use artemis to grab crowley, use Rillionia to grab fusion spell, fusion summon.

 

Weaknesses: Hand traps Go BRRR on this deck, back row cards do get annoying but are much easier to deal with. Going with the Alternate Boss summons, depending on what your summoning, is quite the risk as it can and will burn through ur mats from your hand, field, and/or graveyard. In my opinion with the way I've made this deck tho its somewhat comfortable going second and having Dimension shifter turn 0/1 works wonders against your opponent and their hand traps. you could also run carpedivem to negate monster effects with each xyz summon and add another layer of protection to your exosister and spell/trap removal.

deck_excerpt: Despia; Branded; Albaz; Fusion; Bystial; Aluber; Darkwing Blast; Allure of Darkness; Banish;

deck_description:
The release of the Neos support cards in the POTE set actually made Neos viable enough as a deck but still there wasn't enough consistency. Now in the new BROL set we get a very intersting card that helps boost consistency.

The main principle of the build is limiting the amount of bricks played and increasing consistency as much as possible. 

This should explain many of the ratio choices. And without delay let's analyze some of them:

Elemental HERO Stratos: Now most people that bother with HEROes, know that Stratos is a mandatory 3off. Well they aren't wrong but limiting our copies of Stratos helps reducing our normal summon slots and increases our lets say "flex spot" for adding more consistency boost cards. Apart from that with the release of EN Shuffle we have one more way to go to Stratos if needed and thus we limit his copies.

Elemental HERO Shadow Mist: Shadow Mist is a classic 2off in Omni HERO decks. However, Neos decks have one more way apart from Foolish Burial or Vision HERO Vyon to mill Shadow Mist, that way being EN - Engage Neo-Space. Well in the Ishizu format Shadow Mist is really important since she's able to search Mask Change with her effect, so you may want to increase her copies. Keep in mind though, that the deck can get to work with even 1 copy.

Elemental HERO Spirit of Neos: In my opinion, this dude is the best card in the deck. He can search most of the cards we need for our combos (Neos Fusion, Instant Contact, Favorite Contact, Engage Neo-Space and EN Shuffle) and that's why he is at 3. This is also the reasoning behind the ratios of Neos Fusion, Instant Contact and Favorite Contact. Apart from that don't you guys worry when it comes to summon him, since Cross-Keeper, Engage Neo-Space and EN Shuffle exist.

Elemental HERO Brave Neos / Dark Neos / Grand Neos / Air Neos: The first 3 guys are targets for Neos Fusion since they let us mill Neos and a Neo-Spacian monster and use them as Favorite Contact fodder. Dark Neos more specifically is also a good target for Instant Contact since he can provide fodder for Mask Change and lead to Dark Law, or even negate some monster effect  (with his own effect). Air Neos on the other hand exists in the extra deck as a finisher and he is summoned solely by Instant Contact (providing that Neos is on the field or in the GY)

Concerning the side deck, to be honest it's a really hard case. As you can see most of the deck consists of engine cards and thus siding is hard. All the choices, are cards that can help keep the meta decks in check. In general though keep in my mind that Bystial cards are the ones damaging HEROes more.

Anyways, I hope you enjoy playing the deck and as always we are open to suggestions on how to make the build better!
