deck_excerpt: The Egyptian God Obelisk the Tormentor, supported by his original owner, Ishizu Ishtar.
deck_description:
I returned to the game in 2020, after about ten years away, solely because I saw that my favorite card of all time, The Winged Dragon of Ra, had received a ton of excellent support in the form of Rage of Ra. After months and months of delightedly playing The Winged Dragon of Ra the way I had always wanted to, now possessed of all the powers it had in the anime, I started thinking about the other two God cards.

Around that same time, Slifer and Obelisk received their own support cards, especially Slifer, in the King's Court deck. I immediately built a Slifer deck around the Joker's Straight/Thunderspeed Summon combo, and that deck works very well, and is a lot of fun to play. 

So then I turned my attention to Obelisk, but I was slightly at a loss. Ra had the slime monsters, Slifer had the King's Knight crowd, but Obelisk the Tormentor didn't have anything specific to him. His support cards at the time included Fist of Fate, Soul Crossing... and that was it. Still, I had the other two, and I wanted to do something with Obelisk. Slime would have worked for him, and Egyptian God Slime is made in his image, but I was already doing that with Ra, and I wanted each God deck to be distinct from the other, with as little overlap as possible.

I threw Obelisk into a Monarchs build, which kind of-sort of works, but... not like the other two. Monarchs wants to be its own deck, not have to clumsily work alongside an unrelated boss monster and his support cards.

Then two monsters named Zolga the Prophet and Millennium Seeker were announced. I was intrigued by their Egyptian design, and by Zolga's connection to Obelisk in particular—being one of the three monsters depicted in the art for the spell Soul Crossing. Like the Monarchs, Zolga has a tribute-specific effect, albeit a thoroughly underwelming one. Still, he wanted to be sacrificed for something, and he wanted there to be other Fairy monsters in play... maybe there was a way to fit Obelisk into some kind of Egyptian-themed Fairy deck? I thought that would be pretty perfect.

But after constructing and discarding a number of unquestionably terrible decks that looked like the old swarm-and-stall builds I used to try with the Egyptian Gods, I had to give up on that idea. The pieces just weren't there. I went back to the Monarchs build, imperfect though it was.

THEN something called the Tin of the Pharaoh's Gods came out, and unleashed upon the world two new Obelisk cards: The Breaking Ruin God and Soul Energy MAX!!! (three exclamation points, that's right.) These two cards were clearly designed to be used together to warp Obelisk onto the battlefield, feed him two tributes, and then deliver a downright nuclear payload of field-clearing, graveyard-obliterating, player-burning damage for game.

I added them to the Monarchs deck, and when that combo worked, it was glorious. Absolutely glorious. The deck was already running Foolish Burial Goods, which worked nicely enough with the fact that both cards have in-graveyard effects, but it wasn't reliable. In fact, the deck was performing worse than ever. Having cut six cards to make room for two new three-ofs, the deck was now a mangled build of two different strategies that barely overlapped and mostly just got in each other's way.

So I started looking around for a new home for the big blue smashy God, and I remembered Zolga the Prophet. He had some new company: his old friends Agido and Kelbek now had retrains of their own—the whole Soul Crossing trio, together again. I took a look at the new Ishizu cards, and I started to get this feeling. I didn't really believe it would work at first, but the more I read and reread this bizarre set of cards that depended completely on one of the most laughably pointless cards in the game, the more I started to think this could be an Obelisk deck.

So, I put it together. I playtested it on duelingnexus.com, and... it works. It works perfectly. At this point, I have no doubt that these cards were designed with each other in mind. I mean, when I first saw The Breaking Ruin God, I thought it was awesome, but I also thought, "Since when has Obelisk cared about what's in the opponent's graveyard? Weird..." It was for this, I tell you. These Ishizu-themed cards. Obelisk is pictured on two of them. They fill the graveyard that The Breaking Ruin God is looking to punish. Kelbek can return trap cards from your graveyard to the field, which funtionally lets you search the -Soul Energy MAX!!! trap. Exchange of Despair and Hope searches a trap and lets you activate it in the same turn. It's so easy to mill both players to the point where you have all the resources you need in your graveyard, and your opponent has enough monsters in their graveyard that Soul Energy MAX!!! and The Breaking Ruin God will deal 8000 damage all at once. Sometimes The Breaking Ruin God does it on its own. With Gravekeeper's Trap, you don't have to worry about your opponent getting any value out of their graveyard. Gravekeeper's Trap can be searched and activated directly by Mudora the Sword Oracle. Mudora can be searched by Keldo the Sacred Protector... it all just works. Finally, Obelisk has a deck that is worthy of him.

This is the Day of Torment.

EDIT

Apparently some degenerates had to go and ruin Ishizu for those of us harmlessly trying to bring all our childhood dreams to life, so Obelisk's weird Egyptian statue friends (or whatever they are) have taken a hit. Agido, Kelbek, Keldo, and Mudora have all been limited to 1 as of February 2023. They were all 3-ofs, so that left 8 most unwelcome gaps in the deck. 

World Soul - Carbon can search Mudora or whoever (but basically always Mudora), and Diviner of the Herald can help me bury my now-much-harder-to-find Agido and Kelbek to get all the milling started. With only one of each, it's now necessary to shuffle them back into the deck with Mudora and Keldo, and then search and discard them again with Gravekeeper's Trap. 

It's still workable, but the consistency certainly suffers... so... a big thank you to all the creatively bankrupt, meta-bound, net-decking sheep players who can't be bothered to come up with your own ideas, for ruining the fun for players like me. You suck. Do something original. You suck again.

deck_excerpt: just wanted a simple cheap pure as i can suship deck
THIS IS PROBABLY BAD BUT OH WELL I LOVE PIRATES BABYYYY
deck_description:
This deck is probablly bad. However, I do enjoy making dumb things, so here we go.

I like plunder and think that the resource loop as well as lockless interaction on the opponents turn seems to add harder negates and such to tear which at is very fluid but sometimes may need something extra. Plunder negates, shuffling back plunders for lys fusion, using blackbeard to tag things out, just a lot of little incidental synergies I think might be interesting to explore.

Firstly, card reasoning. Tear is brazy so no explanation there. I cut down the package a little because I want to try and fit a slightly more robust plunder lineup. Dangers are here for extra bodies, interaction, and just generally more ways to get plunder/tear moving. Decided to stick with the four stars only for extra opportunities for dweller or bagoozka as needed. Perlieno is expensive and I don't own it so would only buy one. You can defintley mix numbers around, cut dangers for ishizu, etc etc. However, this is where I am at.

Secondly, why this. I think this legit does have something decks right now not might have, which is hard negates with BEEG MONSTA's. Plunder was always weird due to handtraps. However, way less handtraps now, plus the fact that you can still use the plunder portion of the deck under abyss dweller and shifter seems kind of neat.

Third, what can this do? Currently still in the hard idea phase here, but for example: xenolock into plunders on your turn, get a blackbeard on board with a plunder in hand at the very least. Say you have one more tear in hand. Activate blackbeard to tag into a ship on their turn, no xenolock, so you just get to play the entire deck(just keep track of whitebeard as that's the one hard lock on your opponents turn you have). Cartesia is an infinite fusion loop, so why not have that for lys as well for another option! also, instant fusion for mudragon is a water 4 star that does stuff, so another great addition to the toolbox. Yes floo is scary cause of wind, but that's why we have everything else.

I'm still playing around with this for funsies, but feel free to krib this and make something actually good and lmk how it goes, would love to see if plunder can hang before windship!

But I'm broke as a joke, and only my successful siblings really have a reason to laugh, so what do I do?"

Well, I have a suggestion for you!

...Get yourself banned from all casinos and go see a therapist.

And also do like the casinos and rig the game to be in your favor with this deck!

Perfect for us cowards who want to play a gambling deck, but know that we probably won't have a hilarious victory based on pure luck.

deck_excerpt: Want to learn Domain Format? Check attached Youtube/Discord!

Okay so this deck seems incredibly synergistic for Domain Format. Typically due to the singleton nature, once you've searched something, used it and it sits in graveyard/banish, you have to find other options/plays. This deck though will just never run out of gas. Banished all your eldlixir/goldenland spell/traps? Necroface them back. Banish all your Shiranui monsters? Necro. All your Mayakashi were synchro'd and banished? Necro. I love that I get to freely play the pots that banish too, with zero downside. I love this, can't wait to play it!

deck_name: Ishizu - Spright - Tearlaments post YCS Pasadena (TCG)
deck_description:
No words can describe what is already said about this collapsing format. For all the degeneracy and the number of times we let Jeffery Epstein get away with Child extortion until last year, we indeed deserve this format as punishment for our sins. To make it even worse I can play "Sprights" in Ishizu - Tearlaments. How great is all this though? YCS Pasadena and its results (which will not be mentioned here) say otherwise.

 

   Ishizu -Spright -Tearlaments is pretty simple: Use the Ishizu cards to mill the Tearlaments (and vice versa) to mill more cards; then proceed to make the Tearlament fusion monsters and recover any necessary pieces by banishing the Ishizu monsters from the GY. Allowing you to activate the effects of Nimble Angler to Special two Nimble Beavers to go into Spright Elf as you would normally. Then as a result allowing you to do the normal "Spright" grind game; however, this time with the addition of the Fabled Cerburrel and Abanc can Synchro summon (with any of your other LV2 monsters) into The Fabled Unicore (for hand control and Rank 4 plays). Other neat additions (such as Baronne De Fleur as a Side Deck option, and Number 29: Mannequin Cat in the Extra Deck) are also added for different situations.

Shark/Gishki deck for Domain Format, a casual multiplayer free-for-all format inspired by MTG Commander format.

Beautunaful Princess is the soul of this deck, she can special summon almost every monster in the deck. Using her as the Deckmaster gives me access to WATER or Fish monsters.

I tried to focus the deck on recursion:

  • Whitefish Salvage can be a free Rank 4 or Link 2 with a proper GY setup.
    • Double Fin Shark and another Lv 3 or 4 Fish.
    • Right-Hand Shark and Left-Hand Shark.
    • Gluttonous Reptolphin Greethys and an opponent with the right hand size.
    • Buzzsaw Shark and another Lv 4 in your Deck.
  • Number 4: Stealth Kragen and Stealth Kragen Spawn can special summon each other, if you have Xyz Slidolphin in your GY you can use their effects an additional time.
  • Silent Sea Nettle, Lifeless Leaffish, Salvage can help you to recover some combo pieces from your GY.
  • Sea Lancer can become a powerhouse and then you can setup Lifeless Leaffish and Silent Sea Nettle again.

Cards for further testing:

  • Splash Capture.
  • Superancient Deepsea King Coelacanth.
  • Ghoti's

P.D. Sadly Gishki didn't make it :(

deck_excerpt: An attempt to include Baronne de Fleur in the Traptrix deck this time
deck_description:
Cards you will mainly need:
• Plaguespreader Zombie 
• Baronne de Fleur 
• Foolish Burial 
• Traptrix Dionaea 

You can open with Foolish Burial in your hand, bring the Plaguespreader Zombie to Graveyard, then Normal Summon Traptrix Dionaea to bring out another Traptrix monster. From there, activate the Plaguespreader Zombie from Graveyard, put a card from your hand to the top of your deck, then Special Summon it to the field.

From there, Synchro Summon Baronne de Fleur with the monster you have on the field.

Still looking for ways to bring Plaguespreader Zombie to Graveyard without affecting the Traptrix combo but at least you don't have to wait for the next turn this time unlike my previous attempt. If you have any suggestions, let me know here or in my video.
It is greatly appreciated. Thank you for viewing this one anyways~

P.S:    There are some cards in the deck that might not be here yet but it is the "Traptrix Pinguicula" and "Traptrix Atypus" that is missing most likely.
P.S.S: You can replace the two extra Foolish Burial with any cards, preferably "Trap Hole" Cards but anything will do like Infinite Impermanence.

deck_excerpt: The Toughest! The Invincible! The Unbeatable! Brick Eyes! :D
deck_description: This deck build of Blue-Eyes is mainly about Fusion Summoing, but it can still play just as a standard build of Blue-eyes as well. You're main focus is to go into your boss monster Blue-Eyes Alternative Ultimate Dragon you can go into Neo Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon, but its risky and should only be done when you know you've got game and/or destroy your opponents cards to get through their "Defences" by OTKing them like normal. You'll be summoning Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon & adding your Blue-Eyes White Dragon in hand or setting them up in your Graveyard. Your Spell card Ultimate Fusion will shufflle your Blue-Eyes to the deck to summon out which ever Fusion you need, by doing this you get to also destroy face-up cards your opponent controls up to the number of Blue-Eyes White Dragon used from the field as material which is neet. To search out your Fusion card you'll be using Bingo Machine, Go!!! this card can also search out the rest of your Blue-Eyes cards that you may need IF it meets the criteria listed below, but this by chance since your opponent picks one of the three cards you chosen randomly. Your fairly common Extra deck plays will be Linkuriboh & Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon. Linkuriboh helps by having something on board if you can't Synchro Summon Spirit Dragon at the start of the duel & sends any of your Level 1 monsters mainly the eggs to the GY like The White Stone of Legend or The White Stone of Ancients if you need a Blue-Eyes monster in Hand or on Field. Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon helps by interacting with your opponents plays in GY or on Field with a good defense stat it can also go into your other Light Dragon Type Synchro Monsters if needed. Your only Trap card Ultimate Creature of Destruction is a great way to protect your Blue-Eyes monster from battle or by card effects since it makes it Unaffected by card effects except its own for a turn, it's also a good discard foder for The Meladoy of Awakening Dragon or Twin Twisters since it will come back to be a one time use at least if you Normal or Special Summon a Blue-Eyes White Dragon, but it banishes itself when it leaves the field. I'll point out one of our imposter in the Extra Deck that is Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon, seems like it doesn't fit because how are we able to summon it since its a level 8 requiring 1 Tuner + 1+ non-Tuner Synchro Monsters. Well it's simple by having Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon around we can use its effect during our turn to Tribute itself to bring out our other Synchro monster Black Rose Moonlight Dragon or Ancient Fairy Dragon. By having Moonlight Dragon on the Field and Normal or Special Summoning a level 1 Tuner monster with Monster Reborn Synchro Summoning it or with Fairy Dragon effect by Special Summoning a level 4 or lower monster in your hand, but mainly it would be best to go first with this setup due to you giving up your Battle phase because of Fairy Dragon effect & you can't attack anyways because you're going first. Also if you Synchro using The Whiite Stone of Ancient you can just Special Summon Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon pairing Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon during the End Phase providing protection of destruction effect to your cards on field except itself so keep that in mind. Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon is good with monster negation & gaining ATK if battling a Level 5 or higher monster. One final tip for the deck, if you stumble upon a Skill Drain like card & don't draw into your Twisters to out it then use Dragon Spirit of White to Banish it. But simply "how" may you ask, well as long as these requirements meet in this situation; Your opponent must control a monster for this to work, and have Blue-Eyes White Dragon in hand, you'll simply need to summon Dragon Spirit of White to then attempt to Banish that Skill Drain card to then Chain on top of your summon to then tag out your Blue-Eyes in hand tributing Spirit of White to the GY since its no longer on the field the effect resolves without issue since Skill Drain wasn't able to get to it because it left the field by tribute. That is all, if you liked the Deck Profile, Please leave a Like & Comment. You may also feel free to add me on Discord if you have any questions, NEXUS#6644

For some reason the site isn't letting me put a second copy of Chimeratech Fortress Dragon, just take out one megafleet or the light charmer and put in a second Fortress.

Cyberdragon, OTK, going second, build with a small cyberdark and Therion package. Cyberdark Chimera and Cybernetic Horizon help make this deck's OTK combo much more consistent, and the Therion King, along with Cyber Dragon Infinity, makes going first plays more viable when forced into them by your opponent. Powerbond is a flavor win as well as a great payoff for our boss monster, Chimerateck Rampage Dragon. With the buff from Sieger, you can deal a total of 18900 damage with just this one monster. A few tips for playing with this deck, Use your excess spells, such as Lightning storm and Raigeki, as well as Cyberdark Realm at times, to bait out negates. This allows you to open up the field for your actual combo, which is vulnerable to Ash and the chain-blocking options available for this deck are sub-optimal. Optimal play is Normal core get Horizon, send Herz and Chimera to grave off of Horizon, which will let you send Cyber Eternity to grave as well. Payoff is getting Nachster and OG Cyber Dragon to hand, discard CD to Nachster effect and SS Nachster and Chimera in Defense Position. Discard any spell or trap in hand to add power bond from deck to hand, you may now FS from grave as material cause of Chimera. Now link summon Sieger using Nachster and Chimera, banish eternity to protect your Fusions for a turn, activate power bond using Cyber dragon and Nachster as material making 4200 attack Rampage, activate Rampage effect send two Light Machines from deck to grave, giving it two additional attacks this battle. Go to battle, activate Sieger effect pump Rampage, Swing 3 times for 18900 damage and win the duel. Got all that ;)

The deck functions on two concepts and a few good synergy points.

First off, Virtual World doesn't use a normal summon effect, it's entirely made of special summons. Every part of the Adventurer engine is also over level 3 so it doesn't get affected by Virtual World's drawback.

Second off, Virtual World is very good at dumping out a monster by the name of Beatrice, Lady of the Eternal. Beatrice is, for obvious reasons, really good and can dump aquamancer

Third off, Dracoback can be used as discard for Qinglong. 

I tried a couple of other concepts and this is what I got so far. I'm statisfied with it but I'm looking for other concepts to improve it in the future and hopefully a better side deck. Enjoy!

deck_excerpt: Who says Pendulum died in 2018? This deck aims to bring the most imaginative summoning method to the forefront yet again!
deck_description:
This consistent Pendulum deck tries to (most importantly) get two monsters on the field to summon "Beyond the Pendulum". After this, the deck simply summons a lot of monsters and summons big negates. "Beyond the Pendulum" also neagtes the effects of cards in the pendulum scales, allowing the use of "Performapal Monkeyboard" without it being a scale 4. The number of spells played in the deck facilitates "Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians", and if you draw duplicates then the "Magicians' Souls" engine helps a lot. "Instant Fusion" is a free extender, which in combination with "Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians" can summon a copy of "El Shaddoll Winda" that will not be destroyed.

 

Pros: Doesn't die to "Bystial" monsters, boards are consistent to make and hard to break, can play through disruptions

Cons: "Dark Ruler No More", floodgates, dealing with an established board at times

deck_excerpt: d/d/d d/d d.d d.d.d. pendulum declan_akaba
deck_description:
D/D/D deck list (deck core)

 

D/D/D' are a fun pendulum deck that use almost every monster type. Their mechanic of being Different Dimension Demons gives them really interesting arts fitting of their Arc-V origins. Control, aggro, combo, syncrho, the choices are up to you. This specific deckbuild uses as many functionally relevent D/D cards for you to toy around with.

 D/D's are surpringly modular as a pendulum deck because they can adjust number of hand traps, the tight extra deck space, and side board. Experiment w/ ratios: Some meta decks use bare core & 15+ hand traps). I think one of the best things about DDD decks is that they have a very linear line of play in each opening hand, but no match will have the same end state on turn one. Look up some other meta decks to find the one you like.

Main Deck: Your goal is to set the pendulum scale or search stuff with Dark Contracts to go into Link monsters

Then you can start pendulum summoning to Link arrow zones and Swarm the Board. Otherwise, try to fusion or synchro summon a big board of negates. D/D/D decks are cool in that they include almost every monster type ( with the exception to the niche ones like toons, spirits, gemeni, etc.).  D/D decks are some of the most difficult decks to pilot well; Declan Akaba makes the deck look so much easier than it really is. There are spreadsheets and hour-long YouTube videos explaining the combos. Good luck. Deck core below:

 

Pendulum monsters (lvl1-4 are essential. Open with these most games)  

Dd savant Kepler 3x (lvl 1, scale10, 0 atk) (note pendulum scale decreases: destroy or play long game)

           (can find with Piri Reis map, one for one, small world, etc. Searches the entire DD engine on summon)

Dd savant Copernicus 3x (lvl4 scale1) (send DD monster or Dark Contract with Patent license to GY) versatile

Dd gryphon 3x (lvl4 scale 1) versatile extender/utility (note that as pendulum spell it gives atk boost!)

Dd orthros 2x (Pendulum lvl3; stock removal or a special summon): Use to destroy Kepler in Pendulum zone

           Note that this is a tuner, which can tune up to a lot of good things. Pendulum not restricted to DDs!

Other pendulum monsters: mostly great extenders, late game cards, Not so good in opening hand

Ddd oblivion king abyss Ragnarok; lvl8 monster (best PENDULUM ability, synchro material, stock removal)

Dd savant Thomas (good late game; gets pendulum monsters back and cheats out a lvl8 monster) Also buff!

 

Non-pendulum DD Monsters: Mostly extend into the extra deck. Varies from tuners to fusions.

Dd vice Typhon: Use as synchro material or cheat out flame high Genghis in GY

Dd swirl slime 3x (fusion in hand to get Genghis or any fusion monster) 2x Genghis = rank 6

Dd Necro slime; only works in GY! (fusion extender) Possible foolish burial target along with Lamia.

Dd lamia (extender with dark contract esp Patent license in GY). This is the only D/D dark tuner in the deck, so use it wisely. Alternatively, use hand traps as tuners for a more generic synchro lvl 8/10 like Baronne De Fleur

 

Non monster cards: Note that many pendulum monsters gives boosts for Dark Contracts in GY and on Field. They are great lore wise because the dark contracts summon the Different Dimension beings, but remember:

Dark contract with the gate 3x: Most essential tutor. You get to search once per turn! Eat/prevent the damage

Dark contract with patent license (send to gy to boost up Lamia, Gryphon etc. Also extra deck punishment)

Dark contract with the swamp king (fusion cheater)

Ddd headhunt (awesome removal hindered by the fact that it needs a DDD monster, not a DD monster)

Dark Contract with eternal darkness* (side deck trap as not all decks need to target or special summon).

 

Support/Staples/Side: Archfiend eccentrick (Pendulum monster/removal), your usual Called by the grave, hand traps, etc. Small world is insane. Cosmic Cyclone, Pankrytops (not usually many creatures), Battle traps etc.

For consideration: DD Savant Newton(Scale10/recursion) Dark Contract with Witch, DD Lilith, DDD LaPlace

 

Extra Deck: With Pendulum Decks, you want to link summon so you can start pendulum summoning extra deck monster to Link Monster arrow zones. Monsters can also be pendulum summoned from hand to ANY unoccupied monster zone so long as they are between the pendulum scales. Keep reusing extra deck!

 

Ddd abyss king Gilgamesh 3x (once link summoned you can start your engine) Let your opponent kill it!

Ddd flame high king Genghis (spell/trap negate) Genghises also revives DD monsters in GY

Ddd flame king Genghis 2x (get two out and you have a rank 6 which you can go into Caesar

Ddd oracle king d'arc (gains life from Dark contract rather than take damage. Big Saint. Stops burn decks too!)

Ddd cursed king Siegfried (lvl8 Synchro summon, stop floodgates, also use it to regain life. Not great…) Rank8!

Ddd King deus machines 2x (busted summon atop ANY DDD monster! Not just XE Summon) Destroy contract

Use to set the pendulum scale, summon w/ Gilgamesh) Monster steal opponent’s monsters in chain.

Ddd marksman king tell (XE summon on top of a rank 4. There’s no other way to summon this)

Ddd wave high king Caesar (XYZ summon to monster reborn GY monsters) (XE Summon or let die to tutor)

Ddd wave king Caesar (lvl6 XYZ Summon). Mostly used to give 1800 atk boost to another DD Monster

If you have money to burn, add these generic staples: Baronne de fleur, Divine Arsenal Zeus, Link monsters

Play this deck based on 40 card deck ratios: 1 card = garnet, a card you want to be able to search out of your deck rather than draw, 3 cards are engine generators, etc. Small world or Piri Reis Map searches for any engine, so try it out. Fear Ash or Effect Veiler or Imfinite Imperm, Nibiru you can try a crossout designator combo.

 

Pendulum decks are very unique to their own archetype and often have very specific strategies that apply to themselves and are difficult to make pile decks with. Anti-spell fragrance defangs any pendulum deck.

DDD decks constantly want to extend into the extra deck, so your worst enemy is really Artifact Scythe Lock.

 

A good pendulum has around 60-80% pendulum monsters due to the necessity of being able to pendulum summon from hand. Some DDD decks can use the bare minimum core as previously mentioned alongside Crossout Designator but these decks can be bricky. This can be accomplished because DDD decks only need to the link monster Gilgamesh to start the engine.

 

You have 3 main goals to accomplish with this deck based on your opening hand: DDD decks really want

 

-Gilgamesh: Once you get 2 DD monsters in the main monster zone, you can link them into Gilgamesh which can Set the pendulum scale to 1/3 and 7/10 to pendulum summon more monsters or bigger monsters:  

-Synchro 10: (Baron De Fleur or Beelzeus or Alexander): You’d be surprised how often you can get a lvl1 tuner and a total level 9 non tuner monster on the field. Just be sure to Set pendulum scale to Orthros and Keper (3 and 10) but remember to destroy the pendulum scale with Orthos if you do so.

-Genghis: Use as an extender either to special summon monsters in the GY or just tune up or XYZ summon.

-Rank monster: Ultimately, once you get one XYZ monster, XEish summon Deviser King Deus Machinex

2 Lvl 4’s or 2 Lvl6 extra deck monsters is usually the way to go: Rank into Marksman King Tell into Deus

-example hand1: Dark Contract, Copernicus, Headhunt, Swirl Slime, Othros. Search for Gryphon to have 2 summons to link into Gilgamesh. Set pendulum scale 1 and 10. Pendulum Summon 2 lvl 4s and a lvl2. Synchro summon a lvl10 boss monster. If Ash Blossomed, Swirl Slime to summon Genghis. Set headhunt. Pass.

-example hand2: Necro Slime, Vice Typhon, Orthros, Gryphon, Kepler. Multiple routes: 1)Gilgamesh route Kepler + Gryphon. Rank 4s. 2) Pendulum scale Kepler Gryphon. No recover from Vieler, Ash, Imperm.

2) Typhon Route: Pendulum scale Keper + Orthos. Pendulum Summon Gryphon. Discard Necro Slime, draw 1.

Tribute Summon Vice Typhon, Special Summon Lvl 7 (newton). Link away. Fusion Summon. Build big board.

 

This sort of very complex play and hand interaction and threat assessment is the exact reason why pendulum decks can be stupidly complex. Know the combos and ratios to heart, but also understand the hand traps.

Dinowrestlers are a great deck so long as they can go into combat and enter damage step. In fact, Dinowrestlers only work if they go into combat. It's not like there are ways to return cards to hand, destroy on main phase, banish cards, etc. are there? (Please don't try to build a competitive version of this deck; they don't even work well in formats such as Common Charity).

Your ultimate goal is to link climb into bigger boss monsters or shotgun out dinowrestler Pankrytops. In most cases, Pankrytops hurls himself at opponent’s cards, but in a dinowrestler deck, he can hurl the other dinowrestlers!

In order ensure that you actually go into combat, throw in 3 skill drains and maybe a solemn or two. Skill drain got reprinted so much at the end of 2022 that it's affordable! I wish it weren't because it locks down a lot of decks but here it is.

 

 

Dinowrestlers mimic tag team wrestling in name and mechanic; dinowresters buff each other up and tag out to summon bigger creatures (biggest monster is a Link 3; go straight into Borrel Dragons or Accesscode Talker). Half of the dinowrestler are hand trap battle traps that summon themselves and protect your other dinowrestlers. However, Dinowrestler are fragile and are easily overshadowed but better climbing decks such as Borrels and Salamangreats and the mini boss monster, Dinowrestler Panchrytops.

 

As far as strategy goes, normal summon a monster and try to have a battle trap in hand. Otherwise, try to link summon 1 with parallel exceed in hand and shotgun out a link 3. Scareclaw Tri-Heart x1 is pure BS and xenophobic against anything that’s not a link monster. World Dino wrestling really doesn’t do that much even in a pure build (just use lost world a better combat boost) and really just belongs in the graveyard, so use Extra Foolish Burial. Ultimate Conductor Tyranno and Animadorned Archosaur are just extra boss monsters to deal with because Misc is in the deck and a budget card.

 

 

This is one of my casual decks that I’ve made as good as possible without overclocking it by using cards such as Forbidden Droplet and hand traps. As a principle of deckbuilding, I mostly build decks that are casual or high power/competitive. I… also really like muscle guys and scalies. I know how much Konami loves to use to sex appeal so more husbandos would be nice, Konami.

deck_name: Machina/Train Primer - Kaiju no hand traps
deck_description:
You know how Hand traps can get annoying? You can plan for the opponent's monsters or break them!Rather than stop from the board from being built, break the board? My solution is to use Kaijus!

 

I've always wanted to build a kaiju deck since I started the game and revisit classic archetypes like Mahines, so this suits ms needs. Unfortunately, Machines are a complex pile deck that focus on salvaging machines from the graveyard with lots of good recursion. They are a combination heavy deck that rewards practice and repetitive deck interactions beginning in 2009 with Machinas in the GX era. I cannot emphasize this enough, but this is as close to modern YuGiOh as I can get with an opening turn that can last a few minutes due to the high number of combinations that warrant an entire primer for myself to review.

 

Machines: Rebuild from the field and Graveyard into bigger and bigger creatures. Tank Damage and Attack.

 

This budget variant’s archetypes includes Machinas, Infinitracks, Trains, Gears, and Kaijus. The 7 card Kaiju Package should be replaced with 3 Ash Blossoms and 3 Forbidden Drops and 1 Rivalry of Warlord/Gozen Match for better consistency, except those 7 cards will cost about $270-$400 (which certainly breaks a budget deck)

Note that if you start one of the engines (Machina or Infinitrack) you should exert all the resources in that engine in the main and extra deck, with the exception of the trap card Machina Overdrive

 

Machina Route: Most consistent, setting up the graveyard and board for you.

3x Redeployment, 3x Gearframe, 1x Citadel, 1x Fortress, 1 Ruinforce, 2x Overdrive, 1x Unclaspare, 1x Ancient Gear Box

Normal summon Gearframe: Search for Unclaspare. Unclaspare effect; send Ruinforce, Fortress, or Citadel to GY.

Ruinforce=(recursive OTK card needs 12 levels to Special Summon)Fortress (If a machine can get destroyed), Citadel (if you have big machine in hand and can special summon from the Extra Deck or scared of monster effects)

Machina Gearframe can also attach to other machines to protect them from destruction at your hand or opponents. Run 3.

Rank Machina Gearframe + Machina Unclaspare: Special Summon Gear Gigant X. Gear Gigant X effect: Detach 1 and add Ancient Gear Box (or another Gearframe)

Ancient Gear Box Effect: Find the Infinitrack Engine (tuneller/trencher): Link 1 Ancient Gear Ballista effect/Rank 5

 

Infinitrack Route: 2-3 Harvesters, 1 trencher, 1 tunneler, 1-2 Dozers. 2-3 Heavy Forwards. (add Anchor Drill?)

With 500 atk/Def, get out Tuneller/Trencher just to keep building the board bigger and higher.

Inifinitracks are the best on your second turn to get the OTK. Harvester Can easily mesh with another creature to special summon a bigger XYZ monster. Worst Case scenario is that you open poorly or you get Ash Blossomed so you must normal summon a machine and use Infinitracks as a tribute special summon to build a bigger board. Best case scenario is that you open with Infinitrack Harvester (the most expensive card in the budget deck at a whopping $4.5!), normal summon it to add any other infinitrack card to hand and start building up your board for next turn. Note that opening them by themselves requires you to Link summon (e.g. Goliath).

2x Rank 5’s; Get Infinitrack River Stormer. Stormer effect find ANY machine: Link Away River Stormer to Infinitrack Goliath. Tribute Goliath, special summon Stormer, add Goliath to Stomer as material. Go again next turn.

 

Train Engine: Good All-Around Support for a Machine Deck. Helps the Machina Engine, Gets Rank 10 XYZ monsters.

2x Switchyards just to get a better opening hand, 1x Super Bullet Express, 1x Night Express Knight, 1x Heavy Freight Train Derricrane, (add Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede?)

 

This deck can blow through common handtraps such as Nibiru and Floodgates such as There Can Be Only 1/Artifact Scythe Lock (use Ruinforce or Citadel ASAP) but be scared of Ash Blossom and kill Thunder King Rai-Oh on sight.

This deck can also push through a Necrovalley Graveyard Lock, although it certainly limits some options.

 

Kaiju Package: Generically helpful stuff. 2x Uninterrupted Kaiju Slumbers because your stuff can recur itself, 5 Kaijus including 3x Jizukirus (lvl 10 machines for Machina/Train Engine) and 2 random Kaijus just in case

 

Extra Deck Tech: Rank 4: Gear Gigant X; use one time to get level 4’s out, see Machina section.

Rank 5: Infinitrack River Stormer/Goliath Combo.Loop.

Chronomally Vinama is used as Backup for 2nd ability to negate a monster effect. (takes place of 1 Goliath)

Link 2: Ancient Gear Ballista: Find Ancient Gear Box, Quiliport Genius, Knuckle (all good toolbox stuff).

 

Side Deck: The typical package of Spell/Trap Removal. 3x Dimensional Barrier Like cards. 1 Pankrytops because this deck doesn’t have many creatures swarming the Board. Maybe Shared Ride for Card Advantage, maybe D.D. Crow. TTT?

 

Spice Tech is 2x Ghost Sister and Spooky Dogwood to gain life ASAP because this deck will likely tank a lot of damage if you’re not too careful. If you get Ash Blossoms or Forbidden Droplets, feel free to side out the Kaijus,

deck_name: BUDGET DINOSAUR PRIMER: Scrap Dino Dinomorphia True King package
deck_description:
Dino decks are interesting in that they have a lot of modularity but are largely a combo deck. The core of a Dino deck is very similiar as is the main strategy: find double evolution pill to special summon Ultimate Conductor Tyranno (UCT) after destroying multiple Babycerasaurus or Petiterandons; use Ultimate Conductor Tyranno to book of moon all your opponent's creatures and smash through them. They get very interesting in how they get there and how they utilize their deck ratios: The entire core of a dino deck can be stripped down all the way to under 20 cards with only 3 or so cards that are needed in the extra deck. Some tournament meta decks strip the core and shove in all the hand traps to watch out for and 3 crossout designators, some people try Dino Albaz, Dino Eldlich, etc. There are so many ways to build dino decks, and anyone who says Dino Dekcs are stale hasn't played enough dinos or just been squashed by UCT too many times.

 

This variant of Dinos tries to cover all its bases. uses the scrap engine as extenders and 4 cards for True King as Extenders and the Dinomorphia route as protection. The latter 2 engines are very small but highly synergistic. This Dino deck prefers going 1st just to open a board of floodgates., negates, and destruction. Even though Dino decks can OTK quite easily, this deck does not do well going second against a board of negates or floodgates.

 

INDIVIDUAL CARD/ENGINE BREAKDOWN:

 

DINO Engine:

Main Deck engine

DInos need their normal summon and are thus essential to get as much ash bait as possible.
Example strategy: Fossil Dig: Find Misc. Discard Miscellaneousaurus to protect your dinosaur monsters. Banish Misc from GY to special summon animadorned Archosaur, destroy dino in hand, find Double Evolition pill. Link Away with a link 1, Banish both a dino and the Link 1 or a hand trap to special summon UCT.

The strategy can also be accomplished through Souleating Oviraptor, but oviraptor is more prone to Ash and Effect Veiler hand traps and leaves you with a dead board. However, Oviraptor is a level 4 and can be much more versatile on the field for the extra deck. As far as dinos in eggs go, Baby finds almost engine starters, Petite is used to find Dinowrestler Pankrytops or Dogoron for a big body on board.

 

 SET ROTATION:

3 Lost World// Dragonic Diagram // Mystic Mine// Magical Midfield Breaker
My philosophy with set rotation is that you should have 5 total fields in the main and side deck where just one terraforming is not enough. Any less is a brick. Set rotation is great for knocking out an Opponent's field spell or preventing them from activating any field spell at all. As such, they can stop decks that need a field spell such as Numerons or field spells that kill dinos such as Necrovalley and Zombie World. 

LOST WORLD

Lord world is kind of busted. Prevents you from gettting hit with Lightning Storm, evenly matched on turn 1, slows a D/D/D deck in its trail, etc. My favorite play is going first game 2, activating lost world,  and then flipping a Rivalry of Warlords I had in the sideboard, locking my opponent into Dinosaur monsters they weren't using. 

Mystic Mine helps you build resources and can be knocked out with your own field spell; lord knows when KONAMI will ban it in the TCG

 

TRUE KING:

2 Cards

True King Lithosagym + Dragonic Diagram: Synergizes with Dinos because they let you destroy monsters as card effect, killing dino babies in hand. Lithosagym also banishes your opponent's extra deck.

 

DINOMORPHIA:

2-3 cards.

Use this to special summon Dinomorphia Terrizia: and set the Dinomorphia Shell. If you get hit with Nibiru or a Raigeki, you have to rely on your backrow as protection. I don't own a Terrizia as of October, but it's a card I want. It was $30 for a while when it got scalped in May after doing well in Master Duel, then stabilized back to $10 a few months later, but it just doesn't do enough for me splash down $10 for the card. Replace 1 Animadorned Archosaur.

 

 

SCRAP Engine:

5 cards+  1 extra deck monster Just another thing you can destroy. Best when used as a special summon. It’s a way to spam out level four creatures for Ranks and Links summons. Scrap Golem x1 can be replaced with Scrap Chimera depending on your build. Usually people use one Golem and One Chimera because once you link away into scrap dragon, you can special summon one golem and keep comboing off. However, Golem is a garnet and the Chimera can easily be used for Rank 4 monsters.

 

Expensive cards to consider: Link 4 monsters: Appouloussa: Goddess of the Bow: Mainly used to negate Nibiru.

Accesscode Talker + link 3s; surprisingly easy to link climb in this deck.

 

 

Side Deck: Strategize going first cards and your typical backrow/Dimensional Barrier cards. Solemn Strike is a great budget option.
